<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electric Cherry Harvester Invented in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli company, Stam
Ltd., has developed a low cost, battery-operated tool for picking
cherries, it was learned from the Israel Export Institute today.
</P>
<P>
In using the machine, the harvesting speed doubles the rate
of manual picking and simultaneously, the device is suitable
for collecting such fruits as lemons, apples, grapes, pears and
olives.
</P>
<P>
Ergonomically-designed and lightweight (0.7 kg without the
battery pack), the harvester cuts the cherry's stem to a
pre-determined, optimum length. A special mechanism flattens stem
ends and soften them, preventing damage to the collected fruit.
</P>
<P>
Apart from industrial harvesting, the tool is also suitable
for home gardening. Power is supplied by 3.6v rechargeable
Nickel Cadmium battery pack with a power reserve of eight
hours. During that period, picking capacity ranges from 75 kg
(selective picking) to 150 kg (total picking). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
