<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Blames Chechen Women for Pyatigorsk Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Moscow is blaming two Chechen
women for an explosion which killed two people late Monday at a
railway station in Pyatigorsk, southern Russia, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Vice Premier and Interior Minister Anatoly Kulikov told
reporters in Moscow that the explosion was set off by two Chechen
women, identified as Fatima Taimaskhanova and Aiset Dadasheva.
The blast also injured 16.
</P>
<P>
Both women, detained after the explosion in the waiting room of
the station, had admitted their criminal acts at the Pyatigorsk
station, and were connected with an attack on Budennovsk in 1995,
Kulikov said.
</P>
<P>
He said the two women had been wanted by law enforcement
agencies for participation in the attack in Budennovsk.
</P>
<P>
In Sochi, also in southern Russia, President Boris Yeltsin
described the bomb a "terrorist act," saying that he was
"extremely worried." Yeltsin is on a holiday in Sochi.
</P>
<P>
The president was to meet Alexander Chernogorov, governor of
the Stavropol region, where Pyatigorsk is located, on Tuesday,
Kremlin spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
He was also to meet Kulikov on Wednesday to hear a report on
the situation.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Federation Council (upper house of parliament)
Yegor Stroyev also said on Tuesday that it was absolutely
necessary to put an end to terrorist acts in Russia.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot support, encourage and finance those who use such
barbaric methods," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Monday's explosion at the Pyatigorsk station was twice as
powerful as the blast last Wednesday in Russia's southern town of
Armavir, which killed two and injured at least seven, experts
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
