<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Warns Against Excessive Optimism About Aids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- World Health Organization (WHO)
Director-General Dr Hiroshi Nakajima today welcomed news about
AIDS treatments but warned against excessive optimism.
</P>
<P>
"The wave of optimism that has enveloped the international AIDS
community in relation to the new therapies must not lead policy
makers to abandon their commitment to essential long-term
activities such as prevention programs and the search for
vaccines, microbicides and other effective preventive
interventions," Dr Nakajima said on opening the Informal
Consultation on the Implications of Antiretroviral Treatments at
WHO's headquarters in Geneva this morning.
</P>
<P>
The WHO director-general said that it is premature to suggest
that HIV/AIDS will soon be a chronic, non-fatal disease although
so-called triple therapies, using combinations of three
antiretroviral (ARV) drugs including a protease inhibitor to
combat HIV/AIDS, have shown "impressive results" in clinical
trials.
</P>
<P>
DR Nakajima said the two-year clinical trials with the new
triple therapies were not long enough and more time might be
necessary to indicate sustainability of clinical outcomes.
Moreover, the triple therapy is expensive, costing 1000-1500 U.S.
dollars per month, thus beyond the financial means of many
countries and especially developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Dr Nakajima stressed that investment of resources and efforts
in the development of other prevention tools, especially vaccines
and vaginal microbicides, should not be diminished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
