<HEADLINE> China Wins Corbillon Cup For 12th Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China on Tuesday beat
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea 3-0 in the women's team
final to win the Corbillon Cup for the 12th time at the World
Table Tennis Championships.
</P>
<P>
The defending champion team was so powerful that it only lost
one game in eight matches.
</P>
<P>
World No. 4 Yang Ying put China on the winning track as she
beat Wi Bok Sun in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Yang, the highest-ranked penholder in the
world, used a variety of high-toss serves and strong follow-up
attacks to beat unranked Wi 22-20, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
Deng Yaping, the most successful female player of the modern
era, sent China 2-0 ahead as she used her superior power to carve
out a 21-15, 21-14 victory over Kim Hyon Hui, a losing
semi-finalist at the Atlanta Olympic Games last summer.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Deng, who has added four Olympic gold medals to
her world record haul of 15 world championship and World Cup
titles, overwhelmed the 17-year-old rival with ferocious forehand
attacks and backhand flicks.
</P>
<P>
Li Ju, ranked fifth, snatched the third game against Tu Jong Sil,
winning 21-8, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Li, who beat Tu for the first time at the
Global Youth Championships in February, showed no mercy in the
game. Her variation of spin and speed proved too much for Tu, who
hit a forehand long to concede the match point.
</P>
<P>
DPR Korea, which formed a joint team with South Korea to defeat
China in the 1991 championship final, didn't show up in the
previous two Worlds.
</P>
<P>
"China had an easy game today," said Chinese team leader Li
Furong. "If our final rival was South Korea or Japan, we wouldn't
have won easily."
</P>
<P>
South Korea, who eliminated Japan in the quarter-finals,
suffered a stunning 3-0 loss to DPR Korea in the fight for a final
berth.
</P>
<P>
Germany downed South Korea 3-1 to win the third place as Hong
Kong, ousted out of the medal contention by China, finished fifth
after beating Japan 3-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
