<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Wages and Benefits Up Modestly in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Americans' wages and benefits
rose by a modest 0.6 percent in the first quarter, relieving a bit
worries that a tight job market will cause accelerating inflation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Labor Department reported today that wages and salaries --
nearly three-fourths of total compensation -- rose a seasonally
adjusted 0.9 percent, the most in a year. But the department's
Employment Cost Index rise for total compensation was tempered by
a scant 0.1 percent rise in benefits.
</P>
<P>
Today's reports were being closely watched by financial markets
as the U.S. labor market has become tight in the past several
months. Many analysts have been worrying that the U.S. Federal
Reserve (Fed) policy-makers will raise rates again when they meet
on May 20.
</P>
<P>
For compensation over the year ended in March, wages and
salaries rose by 3.3 percent and benefits increased by 2 percent.
That combined for an overall rise in compensation of 2.9 percent,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
For some time now, U.S. wages and salaries have been rising a
bit faster than the core inflation rate -- consumer prices
excluding the volatile food and energy components. But benefit
gains have been modest, a reflection in part of restraint in
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that compensation gains may soon start picking up
because most of the potential gains from the conversion of health
plans to managed care have already been realized.
</P>
<P>
The Employment Cost Index is considered a good gauge of
inflation pressures in the U.S. since compensation represents
about two-thirds of product's cost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
