<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Falls in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Consumer confidence of the U.S.
dropped for the second straight month in April, falling more than
economists expected and providing new evidence of slower economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The New York based Conference Board reported its consumer
confidence index dropped from 118.5 in March to 116.8 in April.
Some analysts had expected the index to dip to 118 in April.
</P>
<P>
The report comes at a time of uncertainty in the market as
economists search for new data for any signs pointing to the
direction of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Federal Reserve raised interest rates to slow
the economy and lessen inflation pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
