<HEADLINE> Egypt Denies Israeli Coveting of Nile Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today categorically denied
claims that some countries outside the Nile basin, especially
Israel, are coveting the Nile water.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Agriculture and
Land Reclamation Youssef Wali made the statement when replying to
queries by participants in the Conference of Arab Ministers of
Agriculture and Water, currently in session here.
</P>
<P>
"Conveying Nile water to Israel or any Arab country has never
taken place and will not happen," Wali said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that since he came to office 15 years ago, he has
never been asked officially or cordially to provide non-Nile Basin
countries with Nile water.
</P>
<P>
Wali, who chairs the conference, pointed out that projects for
exploiting the river only take place through the approval of the
countries in the Nile basin and within the context of agreements
signed in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The only agreement on the Nile dates to 1959 when Egypt and
Sudan, which use 94 percent of the Nile water, divided it between
themselves. Egypt has access to 55.5 billion cubic meters, 99
percent of its fresh water resources.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which signed a peace treaty with Egypt in 1979, is
suspected of doing projects that threaten to reduce Egypt's Nile
quotas. While some Arab countries, that lie in desert belt over
the equatorial zone, are feared of coverting Africa's longest
river.
</P>
<P>
Wali has said recently Egypt is cooperating with other Nile
basin countries to make the optimum use of the water resources and
ruled out any dispute between Egypt and these countries in water
quotas.
</P>
<P>
The Nile basin groups Egypt, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda,
Burundi, Kenya, Zaire and Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
