<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak-US Ties Should Be Based on Trade Not Aid: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani Government wants
to have an equitable relationship with the United States based on
trade and not aid, Advisor to the Prime Minister on Information
and Culture Mushahid Hussain Sayed said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I assure you we have already abandoned the beggar's bowl
mentality vis-a-vis our relationship with the U.S. as we pursue an
equitable relationship based on trade and not aid," Sayed said at
a seminar on Pakistan-US Relationship.
</P>
<P>
He said a major shift is discernible in America's relationship
with Pakistan in the context of three new regional realities and
the US is now moving toward an even-handed approach to its
relationship with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
First, he said, the people of Pakistan have returned Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif with an unprecedented mandate and the new
government firmly believes that a sound foreign policy stems from
domestic stability.
</P>
<P>
"Economy will be the underpinning factor of our foreign policy,
and this can be seen from the attitude of the International
Monetary Fund which has undergone a visible change since we took
over," he said.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, he said political stability makes Pakistan more
conducive to trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, he said, on nuclear issues the US has shown a
freshness of approach as there is a recognition of the fact that
the policies that are selective will not work.
</P>
<P>
"The US policy no longer stresses the roll-back of our nuclear
program as it did in the past, the illusion created by some
circles in this respect has gone," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
