<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President For Strengthend Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President F. Chiluba
promised here today that his country will play its part, both as
current chairman and host country of the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), to ensure that the regional
organization move from strength to strength to face the challenge
of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the commitment while officially opening the final
dissemination conference on the COMESA International Development
Research Center project.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that the implementation of regional integration
policy will assist Africa's economic performance.
</P>
<P>
He quoted the 1996 World Bank annual report as saying that 30
countries accounting 61 percent of the sub-Saharan region's
population recorded positive per capita growth as sub-Saharan
Africa's gross domestic product (GDP) was estimated to have grown
by four percent in 1995 which was a significant improvement over
the previous 1991 to 1994 and some countries in COMESA
experienced growth rate in excess of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, despite this good progress, Chiluba said, an average
growth rate of four percent in GDP is not actually sufficient to
make much of an impact in poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Africa's savings and investments levels and
social indicators remain below those of other regions of the
world.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "We need to continue to push ahead with our
agenda for economic reform, including reform of public finances
and reform aimed at macro-economic stability to achieve even
higher economic growth rates for the benefit of our population."
</P>
<P>
Chiluba expressed the hope that the research carried out by
COMESA will help policy makers understand regional integration
and assist in developing programs that will help overcome
obstacles in achieving regional integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
