<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 35 Percent of Frenchmen Confide More in Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-five percent of the French
people have more confidence in the ruling majority in running
their country, while 32 percent confide more in the opposition
Socialists and their allies, said a poll published today by the
daily Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 31 percent of the French people said they confide in
neither the right nor the left, according to the poll conducted by
the SOFRES polling institute on April 25-26.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six percent of the people polled said that it will be
"a good thing" if the Socialists win the election, while 33
percent prefer the ruling majority to win.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four percent of the people said that it will be a bad
thing if the leftwing parties come to power, while 31 percent
judge negatively a victory by the ruling center-right parties.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde said that 25 days from the holding of the first round
of the legislative elections, many French people remain
indifferent to or have shown little interest in the election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another poll by the BVA polling institute said today
that 79 percent of the French people consider the economic
situation of the country as "bad."
</P>
<P>
Fifty percent of those polled said that the situation of the
French economy is "rather bad," while 24 percent think it "very
bad."
</P>
<P>
France's public deficit in 1996 stayed at 356.4 billion francs
(62 billion U.S. dollars), or 4.2 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) of the country, according to a report by the
official statistics study bureau INSEE published today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's GDP grew by 1.5 percent in 1996, while
its household consumption rose by 2.1 percent, said INSEE.
</P>
<P>
France has to cut its public deficit to below 3 percent of its
GDP this year to qualify for the entry into the European single
currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
