<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Says No Decision Made on U.S. Arms Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen today said that no decision has been made on whether
to reduce the number of the U.S. troops as part of a plan to
modernize the military.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before meeting Romanian Defense Minister Victor
Quadrennial at the Pentagon, Cohen said that he could not confirm
reports that a Pentagon plan will recommend the Army cut its
active-duty forces by 50,000 from 495,000.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon will issue its Quadrennial Defense Review (QDR)
report next month. A New York Times report today said that the
Army will make the cut and make the U.S. military more modernized.
</P>
<P>
"No decisions have been made at this point, as we'are nearing
the conclusion of the examination process itself," Cohen told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"It is a blueprint for the Congress to look at, to see whether
or not we can reach a consensus for how we modernize our forces
for the future, how we maintain the right strategy for today and
well into tomorrow," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he indicated that the Pentagon may propose closing
more U.S. military bases.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's been clear for some time that there is an excess
capacity of infrastructure," Cohen said. "It is clear by virtue of
the fact we've had roughly a 33 percent reduction in force
structure, but about 18 percent reduction in infrastructure."
</P>
</TEXT>
