<HEADLINE> Tamil Maanila Congress to Join UF Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Tamil Maanila Congress
(TMC), a major constituent of the ruling United Front, today
decided to join the government led by Prime Minister I.K. Gujral,
Press Trust of India reported.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by TMC President G.K. Moopanar at the
party's headquarters in Chennai, Tamil Nadu, this evening.
</P>
<P>
In a prepared statement, he said the decision was taken in the
nation's interest and in view of the expectations of the people.
</P>
<P>
The TMC had opted out of the new United Front government led by
Gujral following Moopanar's failure in the race for the prime
ministership earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
It said it refused to participate in the government on the
ground that its integrity and political morality had been
suspected unfairly by some other constituents of the front during
the discussions to choose a successor to former prime minister
H.D. Deve Gowda.
</P>
<P>
But ever since the formation of the Gujral government on April
21, the TMC, with as many as 20 seats in the Lok Sabha (the lower
house of parliament), had been under pressure to rejoin the
government to make it more stable.
</P>
<P>
The TMC had four ministers, two of them of cabinet rank, in the
Deve Gowda government which lost the vote of confidence on April
11 after the Congress party withdrew support to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
