<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's Economic Performance Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- K. Y. Amoako, executive
secretary of the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa
(ECA), today said Africa's economic performance has improved
considerably, and there is a new spirit of optimism on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
In his statement at the opening session of the 18th meeting of
the technical preparatory committee of the whole, Amoako
described the "emerging and more dynamic Africa" as many
countries are enjoying greater prosperity than ever before; 24
countries have posted growth figures over 4 percent; 32 countries
grew faster during the 1995-1996 than during the 1992-1994 fiscal
period and current deficits have been sharply reduced in many
countries; inflation has been reduced to moderate levels in
several countries; and there is increased activity in African
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
Referring to economic situation in 1997, he said "the economic
recovery underway since 1994 has continued", adding that "more
gratifying still, most of the African countries are participating
in this improving economic performance."
</P>
<P>
On the question of investment in Africa, Amoako said to
achieve a target rate of GDP growth of 8 percent per annum,
Africa needs to raise its investment by at least a third.
</P>
<P>
He said that while official development assistance is
declining worldwide, record levels of private capital are flowing
to developing countries. Overall, private capital flowing to the
developing world increaced from 44 billion US dollars in 1990 to
about 244 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that only about 3 percent of all the
flows of private capital go to sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Mekonnen Manyazewal, Vice-Minister of
Economic Development and Cooperation of Ethiopia, said "this
year's conference picked a very pertinent theme 'accelerating
trade and investment in Africa' at a time when Africa is facing
new and daunting challenges to its socio-economic development."
</P>
<P>
Mekonnen told participants that Africa is endowed with a huge
natural resources potential and account for one-eighth of the
world population while the combined share of the African
countries (excluding South Africa) in the world exports has
fallen from 4.7 percent in 1980 to a mere 1.9 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
He said, during the same period, global foreign direct
investment flows have increased by two and a half fold. However,
he pointed out that Africa's share in this booming international
transfer of capital resources has fallen from 2.3 percent to just
1.4 percent between 1980 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Recently there is a clear signal across the continent, that
commitment to fundamental reform has deepened, mainly involving
an outward orientation of national economies and increased
support for the private sector and efficient markets," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 5-day technical meeting will be followed by a four-day
meeting of African economic ministers which is exepcted to be
held here between may 5 and 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Beats China to Remain Unbeaten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea remained unbeaten
after beating defending champion China 72-65 in group A Tuesday at
the 17th women's basketball championship.
</P>
<P>
The South Korea used a zone defense to separated China's
2.04-meter tall center Zheng Haixia, who hit 35 points against
Japan on Sunday, from the the rest of the Chinese players and lead
the scores to a 38-39 halftime lead at the interval.
</P>
<P>
The South Koreans' tough defense forced the taller and slower
Chinese side for many turnovers in the second half and took the
round robin group win with a margin of seven points.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the only team keep unbeaten after three day's
contests at the current championship.
</P>
<P>
In other group A games on Monday, Japan routed Thailand 88-41
and Chinese Taipei trounced Kyrgyzstan 90-74.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in Tuesday, Malaysia whitewashed Sri Lanka 80-24 while
India beat Indonesia 86-48.
</P>
<P>
The championship are divided into two groups of round-robin
contests. The top four finishers in group A qualify for the
semifinals while the sixth and last team dropped into the lower
class group B for next championships.
</P>
<P>
The top team from the group B will upgraded to group A. Other
teams in group B are Singapore, Macao and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The final top three team of group A will represent Asia in the
1998 women's world basketball championships in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
