<HEADLINE> U.N. Changes Social Aid Policy on Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is shifting
its social services aid policy on Zimbabwe from normal relief
assistance to aid investment and job creating community projects.
</P>
<P>
U.N. resident coordinator and UNDP resident representative
Carlos Lopes today said Zimbabwe, which received an annual aid
package of 20 million U.S. dollars from the world body, was one
of a few developing nations with enough capacity to adequately
provide social services to its citizens.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe fares very well in the world in self-provision of
social services like education, health and the general well being
of its people. It is one of the few African countries with a very
low child mortality rate and a high life expectancy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the reason why we (the U.N.) are no longer providing
relief assistance to this country. Instead, we are now focusing
on long term investment projects like construction of dams and
roads as well as supporting community initiated income generating
and job creating ventures," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
