<HEADLINE> Mandela Welcomes Zairean Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela was "very excited" by the news that warring
Zairean factions had agreed to hold summit peace talks, Mandela's
spokesman Joel Netshitenzhe said in Cape Town today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is to chair the meeting, which Netshitenzhe said would
probably take place later this week.
</P>
<P>
Netshitenzhe said Mandela had been optimistic that both sides
in the Zairean conflict were committed to a peaceful solution.
"He sees this latest development as a major breakthrough in the
process," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, U.S. envoy Bill Richardson said after
meeting Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko that the Zairean
presdient was willing to meet rebel leader Laurent Kabila
"immediately".
</P>
<P>
"President Mobutu assured me today that he is prepared to meet
Mr. Kabila under UN and and OAU auspices immediately," Richardson
said, adding "that is encouraging."
</P>
<P>
He said he would be passing the same message on to Kabila,
whom he was due to meet later Tuesday in Lubumbashi, Zaire's
second largest city which was held by rebel forces on April 9.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on the venue, which followed weeks of secret
talks, was announced by the South African Department of Foreign
Affairs early this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Zairean peace talks would take place "shortly" on a date
to be decided, the department said, adding that South African
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, who has been extensively involved
in mediation between the two sides, would also participate.
</P>
<P>
So far, the South African government has not revealed the
venue of the meeting, but a government source, who asked not to
be identified, confirmed earlier that South Africa had offered a
navy supply ship, the Outeniqua, as a venue for the talks.
</P>
<P>
The vessel is expected to anchor in international waters off
Zaire and Angola, the source said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa previously hosted the first direct talks between
representatives of Zaire's government and the rebels, during
which both sides committed themselves to an eventual cease-fire
and the establishement of full democracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
