<HEADLINE> Levy Warns Syria Against Nerve-Gas Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy warned today that Syria was taking "a grave responsibility"
by arming its ground-to-ground missiles with a dangerous poison
gas.
</P>
<P>
Levy was reacting to a report in Today's Ha'aretz newspaper
that Syria has begun producing an advanced and deadly nerve gas
and is in the first stage in putting it onto surface-to-surface
missile warheads.
</P>
<P>
In an interview to Israel Radio, Levy said that Israel has "a
capability above and beyond what Syria could imagine," adding the
Israeli army is closely monitoring the development in Syria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Israeli foreign minister said that his country
is trying all it can to advance the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the report, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai also warned that Israel is monitoring the development,
and "does not recommend anyone to provoke Israel."
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that he commented on the issue six months ago
following similar reports in Israel and around the world, and
stressed that he has discussed the matter with officials of United
State and Britain.
</P>
<P>
"It is better to try to talk and reach peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
Peace negotiations between Israel and Syria have been stopped
for more than a year, and the two sides blamed each other for the
failure in resuming the talks which were erupted before the
Israeli elections last year.
</P>
<P>
The current Israeli right-wing government has refused to
discuss about the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria
in the 1967 War, stressing peace talks should be resumed without
any "preconditions."
</P>
<P>
However, Syria insisted that the peace process would not be
pushed forward unless Israel commits itself to withdrawal from
the occupied Golan Heights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
