<HEADLINE> Majority of HK People Interested in Sports: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Most of Hong Kong's residents
have some level of interest in sports and badminton is among the
most favored sports here, according to the findings of a survey
which was released here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the comprehensive survey initiated by the Hong
Kong Sports Development Board (SDB) showed that an average of 40
percent of the Hong Kong residents practised at least one sport
during 1996 which represented a total sporting population of about
1.96 million.
</P>
<P>
Data of the survey, which revealed for the first time
up-to-date sports participation of local residents, was collected
through telephone interviews of 4,355 Hong Kong citizens of 15
years of age and above.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 55 listed sports and leisure activities, badminton
was found to be the most popular one in Hong Kong. Other favored
sports include, in order of popularity, swimming, basketball,
soccer, squash, jogging, tennis, walking, hiking and table tennis.
</P>
<P>
Respondents with higher education level tend to favor racket
games like badminton, squash and tennis while elder people usually
engaged in less vigorous activities such as Wushu (Chinese martial
arts), walking and hiking.
</P>
<P>
Basketball and soccer were found to be most frequently
participated by the male respondents while squash was more popular
among women.
</P>
<P>
As for working group, the most frequently participated sports
were badminton and swimming. Soccer was discovered to be the most
popular sport among production workers while students are most
active in basketball.
</P>
<P>
Sport has a continuous impact on local economy. Looking at the
 money spent on sports-related goods or services, over 70 percent
was on the purchase of sports gear and wear. The average yearly
spending on sport of an individual respondent was about 3,000 HK
dollars (384.6 U.S. dollars), according to the findings.
</P>
<P>
And it is estimated that a total expenditure of about 7.6
billion HK dollars (97,000 U.S. dollars) on sports-related goods
and services was generated in 1996.
</P>
<P>
With regards to the perception and expectation of athletic
achievements, almost 40 percent of all respondents have greater
expectation towards local athletes after Lee Lai-shan's success at
the 1996 Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
