<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Chief: Water, Key to Arab Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel Meguid today called upon the Arab world to protect its
scarce water resources for the sake of its security.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab region is still suffering from shortage of water, a
matter that threatens food security," he said in his address to
the inaugural session of the Arab Water and Agriculture Ministers
Conference here.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of water in the Arab world, that lies in the
desert belt over the equatorial zone, is used in agriculture and
the rate goes even higher in countries like Egypt, Iraq, Morocco,
Oman, Saudi Arabia and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
"Water issue is a strategic one and a question of life or
death," he said, making it clear that Arab security is closely
linked to the security of water and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Meguid also stressed the importance of holding a conference of
the Asian Group for fighting desertification in Beijing on May
13-15.
</P>
<P>
Cautioning that Israel is seeking a seat at the Beijing
conference, he called upon Arab countries to jointly bar any
Israeli project on rivers in Arab states.
</P>
<P>
In a message addressed to the ongoing session today, Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak also urged Arab countries to coordinate
their efforts in preserving and developing water resources.
</P>
<P>
The conference is jointly organized by the Arab Organization
for Agricultural Development and the Egyptian Ministry of
Agriculture and Land Reclamation.
</P>
<P>
The conference is attended by Arab League Assistant Secretary
General Abdel Rahman al-Sihbani, Chairman of the Arab Organization
for Agricultural Development Yehia Bakour, Arab ministers of
agriculture and representatives from Arab and international groups.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has predicted that the quota per capita of fresh
water in the Mideast and North Africa per year will nosedive from
3,300 to 650 cubic meters over the period from 1960 to 2025.
</P>
<P>
By then, the Arab states would have to settle with two thirds
of the amount used by Asian or seven times less than the
international average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Hit by Worst Drought in 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- France has been hit by the worst
drought in 50 years since the beginning of this year, and the
country's rainfall in April is 75 percent lower than its normal
level, said the French Ministry of Environment today.
</P>
<P>
The government committee of drought met today to discuss ways
to fight the drought, in which rainfall was reduced by 25 percent
in three quarter of the country and by 50 percent in half of the
French territory over the past four months.
</P>
<P>
March was a particularly dry season for France this year, and
the northwest region of Normandy reported an unprecedented
shortage of water for one century, while the central Loire River
has never had such a low water level, said officials.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Meteo France weather broadcast institute said
that France will be subjected to an anti-cyclonic dry weather from
Wednesday, after three Atlantic disturbances brought rain to the
country last weekend and early this week.
</P>
<P>
Officials are worried that drought-caused forest fires will
break out in the southeast, southwest and west forestry regions,
while 11,000 hectares of forests have already been burnt over the
past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen central and southern departments have taken measure
to restrict use of water and seven more departments will follow
suit this week.
</P>
<P>
Some playgrounds which consume a lot of water, such as golf
courses, some farms and some factories will have to close
part-time to cut the use of water.
</P>
<P>
But officials so far refuse to dramatize the harm that the
drought will bring to the country's agriculture, including grain,
vegetable and wine production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0031 </DOCNO>
