<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Dissatisfied With ECO Incompetence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani expressed here today his dissatisfaction with
incompetence of the Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO)
comprising 10 countries.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president openly complained about the lack of
commitment by the ECO member states, saying that some countries
have done nothing to the development of the organization.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani made the statement at the opening session of the
seventh ministerial meeting of the ECO. Some countries sent
ministerial level delegations to the meeting, but some dispatched
only deputy ministerial level delegation.
</P>
<P>
The ECO groups Iran, Turkey, Pakistan, Kazakhstan,
Tajikistan, Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan and
Azerbaijan. These countries have rich national resources but lack
hard currency and technology.
</P>
<P>
"Several organizations formed before ECO have developed and
grown considerably. However, the ECO has not been able to achieve
the desirable growth," Rafsanjani noted in his speech.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we have resources and can help each other in
the respect of availability and diversity of resources."
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that the ECO is capable of rendering
appropriate services to its member states. He called on ECO member
countries to make decisions to materialize the organization's key
objectives.
</P>
<P>
"Steps have been taken toward implementation of ECO's
ratification, but without enough seriousness," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He called on the ECO ministerial meeting and the next ECO
summit to make strong decisions to accelerate the implementation
of its approvals.
</P>
<P>
As one of the founding members of the ECO, Iran attaches great
importance to further development of the organization and
believes that the ECO is able to play a crucial role in serving
the people of the region, he emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Defense Minister Foresees Three New NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe
today predicted that Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary would
become full members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) within two years.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made at the George Marshall Centre in
Garmisch-Partenkirchen near Munich, Ruehe said the national flags
of the three countries could be raised alongside with those of
other NATO members at the April 1999 celebrations marking the
alliance's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe said he expected the membership negotiations of the three
nations to be completed this year and ratifications of their
accession protocols to be completed in capitals in the course of
1998.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that "the first new NATO members will not be the
last." The door to the alliance would remain open in the future,
he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the German defense minister, the purpose of NATO
expansion is to give eastern Europe the same stability as enjoyed
by western Europe. Stability throughout central Europe was of
benefit to everyone, including Russia, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe anticipated that a binding agreement with Russia for a
far-reaching security partnership could be reached at the highest
level before the July summit of NATO in Madrid. He also foresaw
that there would be a separate special relationship with Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The new NATO to be shaped in Madrid would reflect Europeans'
desire for their own capability to act, Ruehe said. European-led
operations using NATO facilities and forces would be possible in
the future without direct involvement of the North America, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The new NATO reflected a new partnership between the United
States and Europe, which would be expressed in a new distribution
of burdens and responsibilities, Ruehe said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that although the NATO would remain capable of
collective defense, it would in the future concentrate on the
"transfer of stability", on practical cooperation with non-NATO
states and on international crisis management in and for Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
