<HEADLINE> Turkish Opposition Calls for New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's center-left Democratic
Left Party (DSP) Chairman Bulent Ecevit and center-right
Motherland Party (ANAP) leader Mesut Yilmaz today called for a
new government in which pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP) would be
excluded.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders made the call at their one-hour meeting here
as they try to unseat the coalition government and form a new
one.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, Yilmaz said: "It is imperative for
Turkey to get rid of the present government at once. There
is talk of the need for an alternative government model, in
fact this model is quite clear. We have reached full agreement
with Ecevit on the fundamentals of an alternative government
model."
</P>
<P>
He said that the real reason for the current political crisis
was the conflict between the unalterable principles of the
Constitution and the Welfare Party (RP).
</P>
<P>
On April 26, Turkey's National Security Council (NSC), the
highest decision-making body of national defense, decided at a
eight-hour-long meeting that the coalition government should work
more effectively to implement the 18-point package to stem the
anti-regime activities of religious fundamentalist movements.
</P>
<P>
The package was made at a NSC meeting on February 28 under the
chairmanship of President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
A dozen of deputies from the coalition junior partner True
Path Party (DYP) have urged the DYP to withdraw from the
government led by RP leader Necmettin Erbakan as the RP is
opposing secularism advocated by Mustafa Kemal, the founder of
the Republic of Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
