<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Launches Trade, Investment Plan for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration and
Congress jointly launched a initiative today to promote trade and
investment, and catch the potential markets in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
In testimony at a House Ways and Means Committee hearing, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich said that he agreed with President Bill
Clinton that their country needs a new economic policy towards the
sub-Sahara.
</P>
<P>
The "Partnership for Promoting Economic growth and Opportunity
in Africa," proposed by the Clinton administration emphasized
support for countries in the region that are trying to open their
markets.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich said that the U.S. should lower taxes and increase
investment when developing economic and trade relations with the
area, which was regarded as one of the least developed regions in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the hearing, U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky also stressed the importance of the region.
</P>
<P>
"In an increasingly competitive global economy, the United
States cannot afford to neglect a largely untapped market of
some 600-million-plus people, and the world cannot afford to see
a vast region marginalized, " she said.
</P>
<P>
Africa's share of trade in the world for the past 40 years had
declined from 3.1 percent to a 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky indicated that reduction of tariffs and other trade
barriers will help African nations to grow and will also "help
Americans by opening these markets to our goods and services."
</P>
</TEXT>
