<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Calls for Stronger Anti-Corruption Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) --The U.S. Secretary of Treasury
Robert Rubin called on other industrial countries today to make it
illegal for businessmen to claim tax deductions for bribes.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the 55th meeting of the joint Development
Committee of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), he also said the World Bank and other multilateral lending
organizations should halt funding when corruption is found and
tighten up foreign-aid contracts.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the 29-nation Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD), which groups the industrialized countries,
should "support criminalization" of bribes when it meets in Paris
next month.
</P>
<P>
He also urged all countries that "continue to extend tax
deductibility (for bribes) to act expeditiously to eliminate the
practice."
</P>
<P>
The United States is one of the few countries with laws against
using bribes to advance business deals abroad, and prohibiting a
tax deduction for illegal payments after the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act, passed in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said corruption undermines effective use of foreign aid,
encourages others to get involved and scares off foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the transfer of 300 million U.S. dollars from the
Bank's income to the Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency
(MIGA), a division of the Bank that insures companies against
political risk in developing countries where they invest.
</P>
<P>
He said the step would promote a greater flow of private
capital to countries primarily dependent on the multilateral banks
and foreign aid from individual countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
