<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-29 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Only less than half of the registered foreign
investment flow to Turkey during the past 17 years has actually
materialized, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Some 10 billion U.S. dollars of foreign investment has been in
place, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that France was allowed to invest 5 billion
dollars from the period of 1980 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
The United States got the permission to invest 2.3 billion
dollars in the country, while the Netherlands to invest 2.2
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Switzerland were allowed to invest separately 2.1
billion dollars and 1.8 billion dollars in the period.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan will soon issue a decree declaring the port
city of Aqaba a free trade zone, the Jordanian media said today.
</P>
<P>
The decree comes as the Jordanian government has been
encouraging investment and environment-friendly industries.
</P>
<P>
Local media quoted informed sources here as saying that the
proposed Aqaba free trade zone will be similar to the Unite Arab
Emirates' (UAE) Mount Ali Free Trade Zone in Dubai, which has
attracted investment estimated at billions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The sources expected the proposed Aqaba free trade zone to
attract foreign investment and to become a trade and service
center.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's tourism income reached 2.3 billion Egyptian
pounds (about 690 million U.S. dollars) during the last
July-February tourist season, or a 6.5 percent increase over that
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the lastest figures released by the Ministry of
Tourism, the number of tourist nights rose to more than 17 million
during the period from July, 1996 to February 1997, compared to 15
million nights during the period from July 1995 to February 1996.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Canada signed a memorandum of understanding
here today on a Canadian grant of 2 million Canadian dollars
(about 1.43 million U.S. dollars) to finance King Hussein's 4-year
training project in the field of environment protection.
</P>
<P>
According to the Jordanian news agency, the project is an
extension of a previous program started in 1989 after King
Hussein's visit to Canada. It involved the training and promoting
of the capabilities of employees engaged in sustainable economic
development in Jordan, including mining, tourism and water.
</P>
<P>
The new project, however, aims at human development and
training to uplift Jordan's environmental management expertise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African Leaders Satisfied with Progress in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Presidents Daniel arap Moi
of Kenya, Yoweri Museveni of Uganda and Benjamin Mkapa of
Tanzania today expressed their satisfaction that the one-year-old
East African Cooperation (EAC) was on the right path.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Daily News, the heads of state
painted a brighter future of their cooperation launched last year
when addressing a mammoth rally at Arusha, northern Tanzania
where they held the EAC second summit today.
</P>
<P>
"I have every confidence that this time round, we are walking
on the right path and the joint measures we are taking will
benefit our east African people even more," noted President Moi,
also the current Chairman of the EAC authority.
</P>
<P>
He said had the region known 20 years ago, when the
former East African Community collapsed, that the rest of the
world would be moving towards greater integration, it would not
have allowed the community to break up.
</P>
<P>
"Had the East African Community survived, we would, by now,
have made tremendous progress in economic development ahead of
any other economic bloc in the world," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moi called for strengthening the EAC Secretariat so that it
could enroll more staff to carry out its duties even if it meant
increasing its budget by a wider margin.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for participation of the private sector,
saying it should not be limited only to business activities.
</P>
<P>
"We expect them to form regional professional and business
associations in order to advise and influence future cooperation
policies," he told the rally.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan president expressed optimism that once the regional
grouping had achieved the desired economic integration, it was
his hope and dream that political federation for east Africa
would finally be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa noted that the achievements of the EAC so far and the
agreed plans for the future, were all proof that they had hit the
ground running.
</P>
<P>
"The achievements to date, and the plans for the future we have
agreed upon, are all proof that we have hit the ground runing and
that we are on the correct path," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said the east Africans were once at a much higher level
of integration than they were now, and he expressed his hope that
they could still recapture the spirit.
</P>
<P>
"In fact we were far ahead of the European economic
integration process. Perhaps we can still recapture the spirit of
the 60s and early 70s and learn from the past errors," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He commended the east African businessmen for taking the
challenge of the EAC head on and striving deliberately to be
ahead of the three governments in translating the cooperation
into practical terms.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa hailed the political understanding between the three
countries, hoping that a political federation of east Africa
would one day come to reality.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said this time the east African heads of state were
not grouping in the dark in terms of regional integration.
</P>
<P>
He said the gradual steps the leaders were taking were steady
and would surely bear fruits in the future, adding that the
region's citizens should also strive for closer cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said the collapse of the East African Community in
1977 was due to lack of a sound local entrepreneurial and
business base, saying local businessmen were few at that time
and, therefore, did not form a large market.
</P>
<P>
"This time there is no faultering because we have many
well-to-do businessmen in the region who need an expanded market
for their commodities," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moi and Museveni left for their respective countries this
evening and Mkapa will leave Arusha for Dar es Salaam tomorrow.
enditem

