<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Manitoba Hit by Century Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Over 25,000 Canadians have been
displaced by the worst flood in 171 years in the Red River Valley
of southern part of Manitoba province, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Ste. Agathe, a small town about 25 kilometers south of
Winnipeg, became today the first Canadian community to be
inundated by the Red River flood since its crest rolled over the
Canada-U.S. border last night.
</P>
<P>
Though there has been some injuries, the flood has so far
caused no human death, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The extensive floodwaters, called the Red Sea, stretches from
the border to the outskirts of Winnipeg and is 30 kilometers wide
in places.
</P>
<P>
The raging water swallowed up almost everything in its path as
it crossed North Dakota, the United States. But Emerson, the first
town in Canada to be hit by the crest of the flood, remained dry.
</P>
<P>
The province has declared a state of emergency and thousands of
Canadian Forces troops have arrived to help the Manitobans fight
the flood.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien inspected
part of the valley and promised federal aids to the flood-stricken
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
