<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Socialist, Communist Parties Issue Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- France's Socialist Party and
Communist Party today made a step closer to each other in
perspective of the coming legislative elections, but fell short of
calling for the establishment of a wide leftwing government if the
left wins the elections.
</P>
<P>
In a common declaration after a meeting, the Socialist Party
first secretary Lionel Jospin and Communist Party national
secretary Robert Hue called for the raise of consumption power of
the people, creating 700,000 jobs for the country's youths,
fighting unemployment, cutting weekly working hours, and stopping
privatization of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
But both of the two party leaders denied that the declaration
is equal to a common program for the elections or a program for
setting up a new government.
</P>
<P>
Jospin said that the leftist force of France is "pluralistic,"
although they are seeking "a movement of unitary dynamic" against
the center-right majority.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Communist Party members will join a new government
if the left wins the election, Hue said, "If a majority comes into
place on the basis of the general orientations elaborated together
(by the two parties), we will define the project of a possible
government."
</P>
<P>
The two parties also failed to agree to present common
candidates in the constituencies where the extreme-right National
Front party threatens to carry away the votes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
