<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Accuses Foreign Countries of Supporting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Brigadier General Kenan
Deniz today accused several foreign countries of supporting the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing here, he said that Iran, Iraq, Syria,
Armenia, Greece, Cyprus and Bulgaria provide support for the PKK,
which stages armed attacks against civilian and military targets
in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He added the PKK force has been reduced to "a controllable
level."
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war in southeastern
Turkey since 1984, in which more than 21,000 people, including PKK
rebels, civilians and government troops were killed.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant General Cetin Dogan said that a total of 32,000 PKK
militants have been disarmed since the beginning of the struggle
against the PKK.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued today by the office of the
Emergency Regional Rule, the Turkish security forces killed 27 PKK
rebels in recent military operations in Dargecit town of Mardin
province and in Ovacik town of Tunceli province in eastern and
southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
