<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Considering Sentence Disparity Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
says he is pleased the U.S. Sentencing Commission is asking
Congress to reduce the disparity between crack and powder cocaine
penalties.
</P>
<P>
Under the current law, a federal conviction for possession of
five grams of crack, a concentrated form of cocaine, or 500 grams
of powder cocaine brings the same five-year mandatory prison
sentence.
</P>
<P>
The 100-1 ratio for the same sentence has prompted some critics
to say the federal sentencing guidelines are racist.
</P>
<P>
Crack cocaine is associated with mostly black inner cities,
with 90 percent of all sentenced offenders being black, while
powder cocaine use is associated more with white suburbs or white
urban professionals.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced he has asked Attorney General Janet Reno and
White House anti-drug czar Barry McCaffrey to review the
recommendations and report back to him in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
In releasing its report to Congress today, the commission, an
independent agency of the federal courts, offered a range of
choices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
