<HEADLINE> Camerounian Govt Assists Conflict-Hit Oil-Rich </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A mission set up at the
presidency of Cameroun delivered large quantities of medicines to
the conflict-suffering people in the Bakassi peninsula from April
22 to 26, local radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more food were also handed over to 1000 affected
people there.
</P>
<P>
Some of them are reportedly suffering from skin diseases and
malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Prime Minister's Office, the
move is part of the ongoing assistance program launched three
months ago by the Camerounian government.
</P>
<P>
It marks the end of the first phase which included the
distribution of money and tons of food.
</P>
<P>
The phase two, including constructions of roads, hospitals,
houses and schools, will start soon.
</P>
<P>
The government will also provide engine boats, seeds and
fishing materials to help the displaced and other people to make
a living in Bakassi, located in the Gulf of Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The oil-rich Bakassi peninsula has become a trouble point
between Cameroun and Nigeria and military conflicts there over
recent years have forced thousands of Camerounians to flee home,
local reports said. enditem

