<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets US National Security Adviser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen met with U.S. National Security
Adviser Samuel Berger at the White House today.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen told Berger that China attaches great importance to
the relations between China and the United States and he believed
the United States will share with China the same goal: to further
improve the Sino-U.S. relationship to a new level.
</P>
<P>
Mutual state visits by Chinese President Jiang Zemin and U.S.
President Bill Clinton will mark that level, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said China and the United States can strengthen their
cooperation in various areas, especially in that of energy and
cooperation on hydro power and nuclear power projects has even
greater potentialities.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen hoped that the Clinton administration can authorize
implementation of a peaceful nuclear cooperation agreement signed
by the two countries in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen also explained China's position on Taiwan and Hong
Kong and other issues.
</P>
<P>
Berger said the foundation for the Sino-U.S. relations has been
further consolidated as a result of the efforts contributed to by
the two countries since last year.
</P>
<P>
He agreed that both sides should work together to raise the
level of relations to a new level without creating new obstacles
on their way forward because it is in accordance with the
strategic interests of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the mutual state visits of the two leaders are the most
important event in the bilateral relations over the past 10 years
and "we will make full preparations" for their successful visits.
</P>
<P>
Berger also expressed his hope that the United States and China
will strengthen their cooperation and dialogue over regional as
well as world issues.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that the United States continues its commitment
to the One-China policy. 
</P>
