<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cameroun Tries to Curb Spread of AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Cameroun's Minister of
Public Health Charles Etoundi said here today the increasing
number of AIDS cases in the country has made the disease become
the government's preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when presiding over a meeting between the
U.N. agencies concerned and the National Committee for the Fight
Against AIDS in Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 people from U.N. agencies fighting AIDS,
non-governmental groups and other bodies took part in the meeting
aimed at redefining strategies and collecting opinions on how to
better manage the "Fight Against AIDS Program" in Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
The program was launched in 1993 and sponsored by the U.N.
agencies.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the minister warned that by 2000, 200,000 AIDS
cases might be officially declared in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said although the government has taken measures to improve
the situation, there is still more to be done.
</P>
<P>
The AIDS prevalence in Cameroun, with a population of 13
million, was up to 5.5 percent last year from 4.8 percent in
1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 90 percent of the HIV infections are through sexual
contacts, Camerounians should change their sexual habits so as
to stop the spread of the HIV, which causes AIDS, he urged.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed for the U.N. agencies to continue their
support for Cameroun's anti-AIDS program. enditem
