<HEADLINE> BA to Switch Airports in Paris After Security Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- British Airways (BA) plans to
switch all its Paris services from Charles de Gaulle airport to
Orly following a security row with the French authorities, it
announced today.
</P>
<P>
The airline said in a statement that the move is in protest at
Air Algerie, an alleged terrorist target, being given a check-in
desk next to its own at the airport.
</P>
<P>
"The airline has tonight applied to the French aviation
authority for approval to move its entire operations to nearby
Orly from Thursday in a bid to end disruption for thousands of
passengers," it said.
</P>
<P>
BA said that after weeks of lobbying it has failed to convince
the French authorities to increase security at the airport and
that it has no alternative but to look at shifting its entire
operation to Paris' other major airport until it is satisfied with
the security procedures at Charles de Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that up to 60 services a day involving 60,000
passengers will be affected by the move and the airline has also
appealed to the UK government to intervene in the row. 
</P>
</TEXT>
