<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cross-Border Alliances Surge: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Companies participating in
cross-border alliances, which have increased sharply, enjoy much
greater returns on equity and investment than firms that choose to
work alone, according to a new study released by a new report
available here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 15,000 alliances were formed across international
borders in the two year period between mid-1994 and mid-1996, 75
percent of the total of all corporate alliances, according to
Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton. The global management consulting firm is
holding a seminar jointly with the Conference Board, another major
research group here, in Manhattan today and Wednesday on the
subject of global alliances.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the 6,000 alliances formed by U.S.-based
companies in that time have come across borders, the company
reported.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, the number of alliances by U.S. companies increased
at an annual rate of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Alliances are now a central, essential and permanent engine to
achieve growth," said John Harbison, vice president for Booz-Allen
&AMP; Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
Increasing numbers of companies are pursuing alliances due to
the globalization of markets, the blurring of industry boundaries,
scarce resources and intensifying competition.
</P>
<P>
Global alliances can provide growth at a smaller cost because
they lower investment risks, leverage resources and enhance
efficiency and productivity of existing assets, according to
researchers.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which covered 5,500 alliances and more than 500
companies, found that the average return on investment from
strategic alliances is more than 40 percent higher than the
average return the same corporations earn on other investment
activities.
</P>
<P>
The study also showed that worldwide alliance formations cover
diversed areas such as health services, transportation, energy,
consumer products and even local businesses such as electrical
utilities and telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
Alliances often bring together companies that compete, the
report said, in ways that benefit both companies as well as their
customers. An analysis of 2,000 alliances in the past two years
showed that 52 percent were between competitors.
</P>
<P>
According to the researchers, U.S. companies lag behind
European and Asian counterparts both in alliance magnitude and in
alliance skills. "U.S. firms will need to close their skill gaps
in order to become effective global partners and winners in the
global age of collaboration," said John Harbison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Calls for Earlier Solution to Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan today called on both leaders of the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities to work with him for an
earlier end to the long division in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief, who was visiting Atlanta, Georgia, told
reporters that he had met both President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
"If all goes well, in June I would expect to have a
face-to-face meeting. We would invite the two leaders. I would
open the meeting," Annan said during a global forum organized by
the CNN cable news network.
</P>
<P>
"I do hope that the two leaders will come prepared to work with
me to resolve this long-standing conflict," the secretary-general
added.
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island has been virtually divided
into two parts since 1974 when troops from Turkey took over the
northern part after a brief coup in Nicosia backed by the then
junta in Greece. The United Nations has been mediating for more
than two decades to reunite Cyprus under a federal system.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that if he could not chair the face-to-face meeting
between the leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities,
his recently appointed special adviser Diego Cordovez would do it.
</P>
<P>
"If the June talks go well, we would hope to have two more
sessions and hopefully have a clear indication by August or
September whether we are going to make real progress or not," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general's spokesman Fred Eckhard told reporters
in New York that representatives of the five permanent members of
the U.N. Security Council were meeting later at U.N. headquarters
to discuss the long-standing Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
