<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian UN Envoy: Tensions in Albania Have Decreased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Permanent
Representative to the United Nations Pellumb Kulla said today that
ever since the start of deployment of a multinational force, the
tensions have decreased and fewer clashes are being recorded.
</P>
<P>
He added that curfew has been shortened to only a few hours,
with the local police having slowly regained control, particularly
in the central areas, and that some schools have reopened after
several weeks of interruption.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on the Multinational Protection
Force, Kulla called the force a "mission of peace." He expected
reopening of all schools by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The Multinational Protection Force was authorized by the U.N.
Security Council with the mandate of protecting the assistance
being provided by civilian humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
It is also entrusted with the task of providing the security
conditions that are indispensable to enable the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe, the European Union and other
international and non-governmental agencies to carry out their
work.
</P>
<P>
According to Ambassador Paolo Fulci, Italy's permanent
representative to the United Nations, the Multinational Protection
Force has 5,460 troops from Italy, France, Spain, Greece, Turkey
and Austria. Romania and Denmark are also expected to join the
force soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
