<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Tributes Paid to Outstanding Chinese Painter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Personalities of various circles
in Beijing took a last look this morning at Wu Zuoren, an
outstanding Chinese painter and fine arts educator, at the
Babaoshan Revolutionary Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
Wu, who passed away on April 10 at the age of 89, lay among
flowers, covered with a satin quilt elaborately embroidered by his
wife Xiao Shufang, also a leading painter.
</P>
<P>
Wu devoted all his life to painting, and art research and
training. He made irreplaceable contributions to Chinese fine
arts and art education.
</P>
<P>
He had held many leading posts, including vice-chairman of the
Central Advisory Committee of the China Democratic League,
chairman of the Chinese Artists Association and president of the
Central Institute of Arts.
</P>
<P>
Wu, born into a poor family in Suzhou, in east China's Jiangsu
Province, was mainly self-taught. In 1930 he went to France and
Belgium to study art, graduating from Belgium's Royal Institute of
Fine Arts with honors in 1935.
</P>
<P>
He was one of the founders of Chinese oil painting, mixing
Western painting styles with those of China. He was especially
renowned for his calligraphic and watercolor styles.
</P>
<P>
His works include "Portrait of Qi Baishi", "Sanmen Gorge on
the Yellow River" and "Giant Pandas".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
