<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes U.N. Coordination on Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides today welcomed as a "good development" the U.N. Security
Council effort to coordinate action on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here, Clerides was commenting on
Tuesday's meeting on Cyprus of the five permanent members of the
Security Council and representatives of the U.N. Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The meeting called upon Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash to cooperate fully with the U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and to help create a climate of reconciliation and
mutual confidence, so as to promote the holding of direct
negotiations within the next two or three months.
</P>
<P>
"I can see, for the first time, an effort of coordination by
the Security Council, something that was not present in the
past. This is a good development," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted "I believe this coordination should not only
continue but be strengthened."
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the U.N. chief's appeal to both sides to
show good-will, Clerides said "we will continue to show our
good-will."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government announced last week that Greek warplanes
will suspend flying over Cyprus during the forthcoming joint
military exercises as a good-will gesture for the sake of the
U.N-led proximity talks between the two sides on the island.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel is currently
conducting proximity talks between Clerides and Denktash in an
attempt to prepare the ground for a further face-to-face
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish Troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
