<HEADLINE> France Undertakes Part in Laos Dam Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The French state electricity
company, Electricite de France, will take up 30 percent of the
construction work of the Nam Theun Two Dam on the Mekong River in
Laos, said officials of French Presidential Office today.
</P>
<P>
They made the announcement after a meeting between French
President Jacques Chirac and the visiting Lao Prime Minister,
Khamtay Siphandone.
</P>
<P>
The dam, a major hydro-electric project in Laos, is financed by
international donor countries including France, which is the third
largest donor country to Laos after Germany and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed French aid in the privatization
of some Lao factories, and cooperation among Francophonie
countries (countries where the French language is the official
language or the primary foreign language).
</P>
<P>
Siphandone, the first Laotian prime minister to visit France
since 1989, arrived here Tuesday for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet the leaders of some French companies,
including the Thomson electronics company, the Assurances
Generales de France (AGF) insurance company, and the Aerospatiale
airspace company.
</P>
<P>
Next December, the French-based European airspace consortium,
Arianespace, will launch two Lao telecommunications satellites
from the French Guiana space center. 
</P>
