<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Urged to Chart Its Future Work Direction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of Asian and Pacific
countries and regions today suggested that the United Nations
Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP)
should "consider developing a framework to chart the direction of
its future work on development cooperation in the region in the
21st century."
</P>
<P>
A resolution adopted today, the last day of the three-day
ministerial segment of the 53rd annual commission session of
ESCAP, said ESCAP member governments felt that the work of ESCAP
remained indispensable to the region's social and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
However, they also found it "necessary for the organization to
adjust to the emerging new realities in the region and to give its
activities a sharper focus in order to address the changing needs
of members and associate members," totaling 60.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that the commission called upon ESCAP "to
continue to accord high priority to the integration of the least
developed countries, the Pacific island economies and the
economies in transition into the regional flows of trade and
investment."
</P>
<P>
The commission also urged "the developed and the more dynamic
countries of the region to promote private capital flows to those
disadvantaged groups of countries within the context of industrial
restructuring and relocation."
</P>
<P>
Participants in the commission session also urged ESCAP to
provide policy guidance to developing members and associate
members to deal with the challenges and opportunities arising from
globalization and liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The commission took note of "a general trend towards the
creation of a multipolar system in international relations and a
growing interest among the Asian and Pacific countries in the
harmonization of ties between nations, based on genuine equality
and respect for mutual interests in order to solve global and
regional problems."
</P>
<P>
Taking note of major success in economic growth and social
progress, participants also pointed out, "the region still had
many obstacles and challenges. Economic growth in the past had not
benefited all sections of society; large inequities in income
distribution persisted and were even widening; poverty remained a
major problem and two-thirds of the poor of the developing
countries lived in the ESCAP region. It was thus evident that
growth in itself was not enough."
</P>
<P>
The ministers also pointed out, "growth had to be pursued in a
sustainable manner. Rising demand for food, water, energy and
other resources and the spread of environmental pollution were
threatening the region's sustainable development. Unevenness in
economic growth, prevailing poverty, a weak scientific and
technological foundation, and backward infrastructure were
problems commonly shared by many developing countries in the
region."
</P>
<P>
The commission held the view that, "in addition to improved
commercial facilities to the least developed and other
disadvantaged groups of economies in the region, increased
concessional resource flows and debt relief were of crucial
importance in promoting the integration of those economies into
the world economy," said the resolution, titled "policy issues:
Asia and the Pacific into the 21st century -- opportunities and
challenges for the ESCAP region."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Constraints Show in EC Draft Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC),
the executive body of the European Union (EU), proposes a modest
2.9 percent increase in EU spending in its 1998 preliminary draft
budget which was adopted today.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget sets commitment appropriations of 91.307
billion European currency units (104.09 billion U.S. dollars) for
next year, and payment appropriations of 84.727 billion ECUs
(96.589 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
That is 2.4 percent more than this year's commitment
appropriations of 89.137 billion ECUs (101.616 billion dollars)
and 2.9 percent more than this year's payment appropriations of
82.366 billion ECUs (93.897 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The dose of austerity, for a second year running, is believed
to be due to budgetary constraints weighing on member states in
the run-up to European Economic and Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU is set to launch a single currency on January
1, 1999, and the first wave of countries qualified for it will be
determined later this year.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 budget is to be finally endorsed by the European
Parliament in December, after two formal readings by the EU
Council of Ministers of Finance, in July and November.
</P>
<P>
The budget proposes 40.987 billion ECUs (46.725 billion
dollars) in agricultural spending, and 4.331 billion ECUs (4.937
billion dollars) in administrative spending.
</P>
<P>
The draft also plans to invest 5.629 billion ECUs (6.417
billion dollars) in internal policies, expanding funds on research
and development, trans-European networks and small and
medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The budget earmarks 5.624 billion ECUs (6.411 billion dollars)
for external relations, most going to the Eastern Europe and
Mediterranean third countries. It provides humanitarian aid to
countries in need, and for help in reconstructing the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
It also recommends a financial package of 1.3 billion ECUs
(1.482 billion dollars) to help cope with the mad cow disease
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The budget puts greater emphasis on training and education,
cooperation in justice and home affairs, consumer protection and
the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
