<HEADLINE> China Wins Swaythling Cup in Table Tennis Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Double Olympic
champion Liu Guoliang beat former world champion Jean-Philippe
Gatien, anchoring China to a 3-1 final victory at the World Table
Tennis Championships here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Liu used his wickedly deceptive serves and
merciless follow-up attacks to defeat the Frenchman 21-19, 21-14
in the fourth game, securing China's 12th Swaythling Cup for the
men's team championship.
</P>
<P>
China's world No. 1 Kong Linghui won the opening game as he
outlasted 1993 world champion Gatien in three sets.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Kong, who edged out Gatien 3-2 en route to
winning the 1995 men's singles championship and beat the Frenchman
in the World Cup four months later, triumphed 18-21, 21-16, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
Gatien, who has regained the best form after winning the
European Top 12 in February, overpowered Kong with devastating
forehand attacks in the first set.
</P>
<P>
Kong, who trailed all the way until he equalized 13-all,
changed the tactics and often hit the ball to the right wing of
left-handed Gatien, whose backhands notoriously lack precision.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese turned up the heat after taking the second set,
outplayed Gatien with ferocious forehands and solid defence,
winning the deciding set 21-17.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Chila evened the score for France as he beat Liu
Guoliang in the second rubber.
</P>
<P>
The 17th-ranked Chila, who had lost to Liu in the World Cup
last year, controlled the game with clever returns to Liu's
deceptive serves and strong topspin forehands, winning the second
rubber 21-17, 15-21, 21-10.
</P>
<P>
Chinese veteran Wang Tao put China 2-1 up as he won the third
game against Frenchman Damien Eloi.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Wang, who had edged out Eloi in five sets at
the last world championships, won the game 21-10, 31-29 as his
variation of spin and speed proved too much for the 29th-ranked
Frenchman.
</P>
<P>
Eloi made a tenacious comeback in the second game, winning five
points in a row to level the score at 20-all, and then extended
Wang to 29-29.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman played an air shot on Wang's tricky serve and
then returned into the net to concede the match point.
</P>
<P>
China reached the final after beating Sweden in the
quarter-finals and South Korea in the semis.
</P>
<P>
France made the history as it reached its first-ever world
championship final by outlasting Germany 3-2 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Early in the day, South Korea beat Germany 3-0 to win the third
place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0074 </DOCNO>
