<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Attacks EU for Playing Childish Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today criticized the European countries for embarking
on childish games.
</P>
<P>
"Iran had long ago stopped critical dialog with the member
states of the European Union (EU)," said the Iranian president
while addressing the first conference on energy.
</P>
<P>
Suspension of the critical dialogue between EU and Iran is
one of the latest decisions made by the EU member states at the
ministerial meeting concluded in Luxembourg Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The EU also decided to stop the ministerial level contact
between the two sides and continue its arm embargo on Iran.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said that the critical dialog, which the Europeans
considered its termination as an achievement for themselves, had
long been non-existent as a result of pressures exerted by Iran.
</P>
<P>
The critical dialogue was initially meant to enable Iran to
express its criticism of certain European countries, but was
later cut off by Iran due to the EU's failure to answer Iranian
questions on various issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Europeans launched propaganda campaign against Iran and
embarked on childish games and at the end they became ashamed and
held up their hands," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president claimed that "this is an indication of Iran's
real might."
</P>
<P>
"This is a shame for those countries which entered into this
game and then admitted that there was nothing in it," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran has been critical of the European countries
for their performance over some issues.
</P>
<P>
One of the questions posed by Iran within the framework of
the critical dialogue was the EU's involvement in providing
nuclear weapons to Israel and chemical weapons to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Other matter for which Iran criticized Europe in its
critical dialogue was prevalence of racism in European
countries. They regard themselves to be of a superior race and
for this reason their behavior is like that of Israel. They
consider other people to be inferior," the president noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
