<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greater Care Needed for Disabled People: official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China must include work for the
disabled in its general plan for economic and social development,
a government official urged today.
</P>
<P>
China has scored certain achievements in helping disabled
people, Peng Peiyun, a state councillor and head of a State
Council committee in charge of work for the disabled, told a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"However, to promote our work in this regard, we must include
the work in our general plan for economic and social development,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Peng acknowledged that there still exist many difficulties in
work for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
Deng Pufang, chairman of the China Disabled Persons'
Federation, gave an account of China's progress in this field.
</P>
<P>
He said that a total of 257,000 cataract operations were
performed last year, the first year of a program to advance the
cause of the disabled during the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
Also last year, Deng added, 13,000 deaf children were trained,
and 24 million iodine-deficient people got iodine supplements.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that 51,000 crippled limbs were corrected and 114
schools especially for the disabled were built last year, bringing
to 1,493 the number of such schools.
</P>
<P>
China also set up 610 occupational training agencies for the
disabled last year, with 274,000 people trained in the same year,
according to Deng.
</P>
<P>
He said that obligatory proportional employment of disabled
people is now practiced in 226 Chinese cities and 812 counties,
with a total of 162,000 disabled people employed in the urban
areas last year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, some 93 percent of the Chinese counties and cities
and 72 percent of townships and towns have drawn up regulations on
assisting the disabled, Deng said.
</P>
<P>
It was decided at today's meeting that a national meeting will
be held on May 13 to commend collective units and individuals who
have made outstanding contributions to helping disabled people,
who currently number 60 million in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
