<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung's Office's Consultation Draws Over 4,000 Responses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) Chief Executive's Office announced
today that it has received over 4,000 submissions by 3:00 PM local
time from interested parties commenting on the Civil Liberties and
Social Order Consultation Document.
</P>
<P>
"We have had a very enthusiastic response," a spokesman for the
office said, noting that the exercise will end at midnight for
faxed or electronic mail submissions.
</P>
<P>
About 600 submissions came from groups, more than 3,200 from
individuals and some 200 on the Internet. Further submissions
mailed up to today were expected to arrive over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
"The range of suggestions will be analyzed and considered
before any bills are finalized," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
About 70 groups had met Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa,
Secretary of Justice Elsie Leung and Secretary for Policy
Coordination in Tung's office Michael Suen during the three-week
consultation starting April 9.
</P>
<P>
These included business and professional groups, district-based
associations, women's groups and associations, media groups,
political parties or associations, university groups, labor
associations and humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
More than 26,000 copies of the consultation document were
distributed to tap the local community's views over proposed
amendments to the Societies Ordinance and the Public Order
Ordinance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
