<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Remain International Center of Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will remain an
international center of finance and the best platform for
companies wanting to do business in the Asia-Pacific, said John
Bond, chief executive of the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking
Corporation (HSBC) plc.
</P>
<P>
Delivering the key-note address at a seminar -- Hong Kong at
the Heart of Asia's Finance, he said that he believed Hong Kong
matches the criteria he had listed better than any other financial
center in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council (TDC) in London Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the future, he said that the Basic Law for the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) ensures that after July
1, 1997, the HKSAR Government on its own will formulate monetary
and financial policies, safeguard the free operation of financial
business and financial markets and regulate them in accordance
with law.
</P>
<P>
"I do not know of any other place in the world that has an
international treaty and constitution that explicitly guarantees
its position as an international center of finance into the next
century," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the message today is twofold: first, have confidence
in Hong Kong because of our track record and because we have
confidence in ourselves. Second, there will be a lot of
opportunities opening up over the next 10 years, and Hong Kong
makes sense if you are looking for a financial partner in Asia."
</P>
<P>
According to the TDC, Hong Kong is currently the second largest
banking center in Asia, and is host to 85 of the world's top 100
banks in terms of capitalization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
