<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl's Party Denies French Oil Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 30 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
party today angrily denied French news reports that it had
received millions of dollars in illicit payments from the French
oil company, Elf-Aquitaine.
</P>
<P>
"This is an especially vicious rumor, ... an ugly fabrication
in which there is nothing," said Christian Democratic Union (CDU)
General Secretary Peter Hintze.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the CDU had never received money,
directly or indirectly, from Elf-Aquitaine. The allegations were
probably an attempt to undermine the good Franco-German relations
in the run-up to French general elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
The French newspaper Le Parisien reported on Tuesday that
Elf-Aquitaine had paid 13.5 million marks (about 7.8 million U.S.
dollars) in commissions for the purchase of former East Germany's
state-owned "Minol" gas station chain, and the takeover of the
Leuna refinery in eastern Saxony-Anhalt state after the 1990
German reunification.
</P>
<P>
A large part of the money went to Germany and was meant for the
CDU, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The French news magazine, Le Nouvel Observateur, also reported
that the money had been used to help finance Kohl's 1994
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Under German law, all contributions to political parties over
20,000 marks must be made public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
