<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, France One-all in Men's Team Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Patrick Chila evened
the score at 1-1 for France as he beat double Olympic champion Liu
Guoliang at the men's team final of the World Table Tennis
Championships here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 17th-ranked Frenchman, who had lost to Liu in the World Cup
last year, controled the game with clever returns to Liu's
deceptive serves and strong topspin forehands, winning the second
rubber 21-17, 15-21, 21-10.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Kong Linghui had put the defending champion China
one up after beating Jean-Philippe Gatien in the opening game.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Kong, who edged out 1993 world champion Gatien
3-2 en route to winning the men's singles championship and beat
the Frenchman again in the World Cup in 1995, took the opening
game 18-21, 21-16, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
Gatien, who has regained the best form after winning the
European Top 12 in February, overpowered Kong with devastating
forehand attacks in the first set.
</P>
<P>
Kong, who trailed all the way until he evened the score at
13-13, changed the tactics and often hit the ball to the right
wing of left-handed Gatien, whose backhands notoriously lack
precision.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese turned up the heat after taking the second set,
outplayed Gatien with ferocious forehands and solid defence,
winning the deciding set 21-17.
</P>
<P>
Chinese veteran Wang Tao, ranked sixth in the world, plays
against Damien Eloi in the third game. Wang had ousted the
Frenchman in five sets in the last world championships.
</P>
<P>
Kong, reigning world singles champion, will confront with Chila
in the fifth game if both make that far.
</P>
<P>
Kong had downed Chila in a group match at the 1996 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
China, which has won the Swaythling Cup for the men's team
championship for 12 times, reached the final after beating Sweden
in the quarter-finals and South Korea in the semis.
</P>
<P>
France made the history as it reached its first-ever world
championship final by outlasting Germany 3-2 on Tuesday
semifinal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
