<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Simplifies Shenzhen Formalities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The animal and plant quarantine
departments are to withdraw tomorrow from the Man Kam To and Sha
Tau Kok ports of entry, paving the way for further simplification
of procedures at ports of entry in this, China's first special
economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The border quarantine offices have been withdrawn from the
city's land ports of entry over the past two years. The animal and
plant quarantine departments followed suit beginning last year.
</P>
<P>
The city put forward a pilot reform plan for its port
management system, which has been approved by the State Council.
</P>
<P>
From tomorrow, drivers coming and going through the ports of
entry will not have to stop for the checks they had to undergo
four times before. Instead, they will fill in declaration forms
for the vehicles and goods concerned before exit and entry,
getting ready for spot checks.
</P>
<P>
Drivers and owners of plants and vegetable products are
required to pass check procedures beforehand. The animal
quarantine departments will increase checks at port of entry areas
and cargo destinations.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has three land ports of entry, handling more than
eight million vehicles annually, accounting for 70 percent of the
country's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
