<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Presidents' Summit for America's Future closed in
Philadelphia Tuesday as it began, with a dizzling mixture of good
intentions, high-wattage celebrity and hyperbolic rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
-- After months of internal debate, the U.S. Sentencing
Commission recommended Tuesday that the wide gap between penalties
for crack and powder cocaine crimes be reduced, saying the current
stiffer crack punishments "cannot be justified."
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The authorities said they were highly hopeful of arranging a
peaceful surrender by the militant Texas group that took two
hostages three days ago. But many of the 80 neighbors forced from
their homes by the standoff angrily demanded that the state move
against the group.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Defense Secretary William Cohen said additional base closing
may be among the recommendations of a Pentagon review now under
way, saying troop strength has fallen in recent years and may
continue to do so. The U.S. has already closed 97 major bases
since 1988, and an early reaction in Congress suggests more
closing would face resistance.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- A star witness in the Oklohoma City bombing trial Tuesday
described how an angry Timothy McVeigh disclosed his plan to
destroy the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The stock market scored a near-record gain Tuesday on news
that labor costs remain low despite strong wage growth, spurring
hopes that the Federal Reserve will not raise interest rates
again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
