<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Random Drug Testing to Be Held in HK's Pro Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's professional
football players could face random drug testing next season, the
Hong Kong Football Association (HKFA) has ruled.
</P>
<P>
The sport's local governing body came to the decision after the
Asian Football Confederation (AFC) called last Saturday its member
associations to fight against drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
The AFC had encouraged its memberships to start random doping
tests on players in their respective leagues, especially those on
the Olympics and the World Cup squads.
</P>
<P>
And the AFC officials said the organization's medical committee
would formulate rules and regulations for doping tests.
</P>
<P>
HKFA Chairman Victor Hui said that by the latest decision on
drug testing, the association is supporting the AFC on the
anti-drug battle.
</P>
<P>
But Hui said details of the plan are yet to be discussed and
finalized and he did not expect a large-size doping test program
due to HKFA's limited resources and staffing.
</P>
<P>
HKFA Secretary-General Vincent Yuen said random doping tests
might be arranged for all domestic games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
