<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Beauty Products Company Eyeing China Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- France's L'Oreal, one of the
world's leading beauty products companies, has announced that it
will increase its investment in China to get a bigger part of
China's make-up business.
</P>
<P>
L'Oreal now has 12 percent of the world's cosmetics market, and
has been exploring the Chinese market since the '80s, and intends
to improve its business in this market, which has great potential,
according to Paolo Gasparrini, general manager of L'Oreal China.
</P>
<P>
In China L'Oreal still faces stiff competition from such
well-known cosmetics companies as the US's P&AMP;G, Estee Lauder, and
Avon, Britain's Unilever, and Japan's Shiseido, said Gasparrini.
</P>
<P>
It has cooperated with the Suzhou Medical College in east
China's Jiangsu Province, setting up a joint venture in 1996 to
produce Maybelline products, the big name American company that
was purchased by L'Oreal.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on L'Oreal's second factory in China began in
Suzhou this month. The first and second phases are expected to
cost more than 40 million US dollars. The first phase is expected
to be completed by the end of next year, after which 30 million
products can be produced annually. Production capacity of the
factory is expected to rise to 150 million items ultimately.
</P>
<P>
In China, L'Oreal will focus on the barber and beauty shop, and
common-use and expensive cosmetic business. It has set up L'Oreal
China Co., Ltd. in Shanghai, a research center in Suzhou, and
training centers in Shanghai and Guangzhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
