<HEADLINE> Macao Trade Unions to Work for Stable Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Macao trade unions will make
further contributions to a stable transition in Macao by working
in cooperation with the government and all walks of life, a top
trade union leader said today.
</P>
<P>
Pun Hun Veng, chairman of the Macao Federation of Trade
Unions, said in a gathering marking the May 1 International Labor
Day that trade unions in Macao are concerned not only in workers'
life, but a stable transition in the territory.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the government to take effective measures as soon as
possible to improve public security environment so that a stable
transition can be achieved," he said.
</P>
<P>
A wave of triad-related violence has jolted the territory since
 late last year, causing great concern among local citizens. Local
 security authorities have vowed to curb the spread of organized
crimes and launched several major attacks so far.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the trade union chairman urged the government to
help create more job opportunities to ease the pressure of a high
jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment has become an outstanding social problem," he
said, blaming a continuous economic slowdown in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the government will take concrete actions to help the
unemployed find new jobs, and improve workers' living standard,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Soares Monge, secretary for security of the Macao
government, attended today's reception on behalf of the governor
who is on a visit to Brazil. Other celebrities included Wang
Qiren, director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
