<HEADLINE> Trade Fair Strikes 10 Billion US Dollars-Worth of Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Deals worth nearly 10 billion
US dollars were struck during the 81st China Export Commodities
Fair, which ended today in this capital city of south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The figure was nearly the same as that of last year, according
to the organizer.
</P>
<P>
Like the previous fairs, transactions clinched with countries
of the European Union accounted for the largest proportion, at
25.7 percent of the total. Trading with Hong Kong and Macao made
up 15.7 percent, while that with the United States was 12.7
percent, down slightly from last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Asean (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
countries, the Gulf states, Latin America, Africa, the former
Soviet Union and other east European countries increased,
signifying a diversification of China's export markets.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, exports of light industrial products and
handicrafts led all the others, with a proportion of 33.7 percent
of the total. Machinery and electronics again exceeded textiles and
garments as the second-largest export fields, accounting for about 26
percent of the total, up two percentage points from the previous
fair.
</P>
<P>
Exports of grain, edible oil, farm produce, chemicals and
medicines rose markedly, the organizer said.
</P>
<P>
More than 60,300 business people visited the fair, the largest
number in the history of the annual event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
