<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Opens New Cross-Harbor Tunnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Western Harbor Tunnel
(WHT), Hong Kong's largest cross-harbor tunnel constructed between
Sai Ying Pun and the West Kowloon Reclamation, officially opened
to public traffic today, three months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
Being Hong Kong's first dual 3-lane harbor tunnel, the WHT
increases Hong Kong's combined cross-harbor tunnel capacity by 75
percent.
</P>
<P>
It will also help significantly reduce traffic congestion at
the two existing tunnels and in the urban areas adjacent to them
since queues cause serious interference with non-tunnel traffic in
rush hours.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the new tunnel said that the tunnel's practical
capacity is 180,000 vehicles a day, 50 percent greater than each
of the existing tunnels. This is sufficient to support predicted
traffic levels and is intended to meet Hong Kong's cross-harbor
transport needs well into the 21st century, he added.
</P>
<P>
With a total cost of 7.5 billion HK dollars (962 million US
dollars), the 2-km tunnel connects the major population centers
of Hong Kong with the container ports in Kwai Chung, the new
airport at Chek Lap Kok, and opens up the Northwestern "New
Territories" and then connects with the new super-highway to
Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
This is the second major traffic infrastructure Hong Kong
completed this week. On Sunday Hong Kong opened its Tsing Ma
Bridge -- the world's longest suspension bridge carrying both
road and rail traffic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
