<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEZ Urged to Speed Up Reform Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing
has called on officials of China's special economic zones (SEZ) to
speed up reforms and expand their exemplary role in experimenting
with China's economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Li made the call in a special letter written to a national SEZ
forum held in Qionghai City, south China's Hainan Province, from
April 23 to 24.
</P>
<P>
Leading local officials from China's five special economic
zones of Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Xiamen, Shantou, Hainan, as well as
Pudong New Area of Shanghai, attended the two-day forum which was
sponsored by the SEZ Affairs Office of the State Council, the
country's highest governing body.
</P>
<P>
The vice premier also urged participants to concentrate their
energy on working out ways for acquiring new experience under
the new situation, and to advance economic restructuring, foster
main local industrial businesses that cater to their respective
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Li asked participants to pay special attention to the
development of high-tech-intensive industrial sectors and to
strive to improve the efficiency and standard of the
export-oriented economy, so as to enhance their respective
competitiveness on the international market.
</P>
<P>
Information from the forum disclosed that last year, the five
SEZ generated 215.5 billion yuan of gross domestic product (GDP),
a rise of 14.3 percent over 1995, or five percentage points more
than the national average growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Pudong New Area also generated 51.02 billion yuan of GDP in
1996, a rise of 20.2 percent over 1995. Pudong created 113.2
billion yuan of industrial output value in 1996, up 18.2 percent
over 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
