<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Lowers Economic Growth Predictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has revised the
country's economic growth forecast for 1997 from 7.1 percent to
6.6 percent, and the current account deficit from 7.7 percent of
gross domestic product (GDP) to 6.7 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts made late last year had projected economic growth for
1997 at 7.1 percent, but the figure was later revised downward to
6.8 percent, following the government's decision to make deep
fiscal budget cuts worth 59 billion baht (2.36 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's economic growth was 6.8 percent, the
current account deficit was about 8.3 percent of GDP, and
inflation was 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The National Economic and Social Development Board, the
country's economic and social planning agency, expected that the
current account deficit and inflation situation will be eased this
year.
</P>
<P>
While current account deficit is expected to drop one
percentage point from the forecast made late last December, from
7.7 percent of GDP down to 6.7 percent of GDP, inflation is also
expected to be lower than the earlier forecast of 5 percent, at
4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The revision was made taking into consideration of economic
performance during the first quarter of this year, which slowed
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
The revision was also due to new data on GDP figures dating to
1990 and revised bank of Thailand data on foreign trade, which
showed only a 0.2 percent growth last year. The bank also lowered
its forecast for external trade growth for 1997 from a previous
forecast of 11.6 percent, to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The board suggested that current macroeconomic policies should
be maintained, particularly in the area of fiscal discipline. More
budget cuts by both the government and state enterprises are
likely necessary.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government should work to improve the
performance of state enterprises in a bid to maintain state
revenue levels, the board said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
