<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Pakistani President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-Pakistani relationship
has entered a new stage, Chinese Premier Li Peng said during a
meeting with visiting Pakistani President Farooq Ahmed Khan
Leghari here today.
</P>
<P>
Li recalled his meetings and talks with Leghari in 1994 and
1995 and appreciated Leghari's contribution to development of
Sino-Pakistani relations. Li said: "I believe your current visit
will help promote the development of bilateral friendly
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
During the past decades, Li said, both countries have made
joint efforts to push forward bilateral relations into a new stage
characterized by all-round cooperation and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
China and Pakistan have carried on fruitful cooperation in a
variety of areas, he said, adding that both countries have
supported and coordinated with each other in international affairs
all along.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Chinese government, Li extended appreciation
for the support given by the Pakistani government in such issues
as human rights, Taiwan, and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
He described the Sino-Pakistani cooperation as a "good example"
of mutually beneficial cooperation between countries with
different social systems.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation between China and Pakistan has a wide field
and a bright prospect," he said, adding that given the
circumstances of market economy, the two countries' businesses
should increase cooperation and work together to seek new channels
and structures for bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Leghari said Pakistan consistently considers China a "true
friend" and China has provided a great amount of aid for the
country. He added that Pakistan and China share much in common and
it is significant for both of them to continue to increase
friendly cooperation on the basis of mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan treasures the tradition of friendship between the two
countries, and expects cooperation in more areas, especially in
trade and economy.
</P>
<P>
He agreed with China's proposal for further cooperation between
enterprises of the two countries and welcomed Chinese enterprises
to participate in technological improvement, investment, and other
cooperative undertankings in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"The international affairs are numerous and complicated," Li
said, adding that China shares the same view with Pakistan that
the multipolarization in the world is conducive to peace and
common development. Every country has the right to be master of
its own destiny, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Li said China is ready to work hand in hand with Pakistan to
build a relationship of all-round cooperation looking towards the
21th century.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation Wu Yi and Pakistani Minister of Commerce, Industries,
and Investment Muhammad Ishaq Dar exchanged in-depth views on some
problems concerning bilateral trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
