<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Majority Support for Society Registration: HK Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- A majority of Hong Kong
residents hold the view that the local society should apply to the
government for registration and a public procession should be
approved beforehand by the police, a recent survey shows.
</P>
<P>
The poll aims to demonstrate public opinions of the Civil
Liberties and Social Order Consultation Document issued by the
Chief Executive Office of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) early this month. The consultation, scheduled to
end today, is to invite public comments on proposals to amend the
Societies Ordinance and the Public Order Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
Based on a random selection, the Hong Kong Public Opinion
Research Center telephoned more than 2,000 local residents aged 18
or above on April 24 and succeeded in interviewing 780.
</P>
<P>
About 82 percent of the interviewees believed that society
should apply to the government for registration, said Francis
Hong, manager of the research center.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that nearly 79 percent was in favor of
the proposal that a public procession should first gain the nod of
the police.
</P>
<P>
Hong said that public opinions part on connection between local
and foreign political organizations.
</P>
<P>
As to whether local political parties should be banned from
accepting foreign financial support, half of the interviewees
said "no" while one third said "yes".
</P>
<P>
However, 60 percent agreed that foreign organizations should be
 banned from exerting influence over local political
parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nokia's First-Quarter Earning Soars Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Nokia, the world's biggest
mobile phone maker, reported a pretax profit of 1.45 billion
markka (284 million U.S. dollars) in the first quarter, triple the
amount in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic rise was mainly due to a 58 percent growth in the
net sales of mobile phones in the first quarter by the Finnish
company, which amounted to 6.1 billion markka (1.2 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Total net sales during the January-March period came to 11.3
billion markka (2.2 billion dollars), 43 percent up from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
However, its first-quarter performance slid a little from the
previous quarter, which registered a pretax profit of 1.6 billion
markka (365 million dollars), and net sales of 12.6 billion markka
(2.8 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nokia's pretax profit fell by 21 percent to 3.9 billion markka
(860 million dollars) last year, but its sales started to pick up
at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Based in Helsinki, Nokia has about 33,000 employees in 45
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
