<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President: Turkey Supports Romania's Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel reaffirmed Turkey's active support to Romania's early
accession to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
According to a joint press statement issued here today,
Demirel and visiting Romanian President Emil Constantinescu
believed that the European integration process should be an
all-embracing one and that a broad congruence should be achieved
among the major Euro-Atlantic institutions, namely the NATO, the
European Union (EU) and the Western European Union (WEU).
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu arrived in Istanbul, the largest city in
Turkey, Monday to participate in the opening session of the
business conference of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC)
and to pay a three-day state visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
This was the first visit to Turkey by Constantinescu since he
was elected as Romanian president.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents said that southeastern Europe should become
a region of peace, stability and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They said that all countries of the region should base their
relationship toward each other on the principle of respect for
territorial integrity, inviolability of border and
non-interference in the internal affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the two presidents were satisfied with
the level of bilateral relations which are developing on the
solid basis of mutual friendship and understanding existing
between Turkey and Romania.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that the further development of economic and
trade ties should be made between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Romania Tuesday signed a free trade agreement and
two accords on cooperation in the fields of animal health and
plant protection following official talks between Demirel and
Constantinescu.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the two presidents agreed to
hold regular reciprocal visits twice every year, adding that
Demirel accepted Constantinescu's invitation and would pay a
state visit to Romania before the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
