<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Airport Authority Awards Contract for Runway Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Airport Authority
(AA) has awarded the contract for Northern Runway works at the new
airport at Chek Lap Kok, the AA said today.
</P>
<P>
The contract was awarded to the ACG Joint Venture (ACGJV),
comprising AMEC of Britain, Fujian of the People's Republic
of China, and Hellit and Woerner Bau AG of Germany.
</P>
<P>
The project includes construction of the Northern Runway and
taxiways, drainage, irrigation, emergency power generation, an
electrical distribution system, potable water and fire mains,
facilities for the Civil Aviation Department and Hong Kong
Observatory, marine approach structures, grassing and
miscellaneous works, AA said.
</P>
<P>
The ACGJV contract, worth 995 million HK dollars (128 million
U.S. dollars), including options for additional projects, will take
19 months to complete.
</P>
<P>
AA Chief Executive Officer Henry Townsend said that the new
airport's Phase 2 project, which comprises of the second runway
and the passenger terminal's northwest concourse extension, will
enable the declared runway capacity at the new airport to increase
from 37/38 aircraft movements per hour to 50 movements per hour
within the first year of commissioning.
</P>
<P>
"Not only will the timely construction of the Northern Runway
benefit the aviation and tourism industries, but the additional
capacity and enhanced efficiency it will provide will flow on
into Hong Kong's wider economy," he said, adding "It will reinforce
confidence in the new airport as a pre-eminent hub for
international and regional aviation."
</P>
<P>
The works would not have any impact on the completion of the
first phase of the airport project targeted for completion and
opening in April 1998, and nor would additional government equity
be required.  
</P>
</TEXT>
