<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Closes Ranks of Muslims, Copts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said today that Christian Copts are always an integral part of
Egypt, in an apparent gesture to placate worries about growing
grudge between the country's Muslims and Copts.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt's Copts are part and parcel of the tightly-interwoven
texture of the Egyptian community," said Mubarak in his speech on
May Day celebrations.
</P>
<P>
But Mubarak warned that there were still attempts to foment and
instigate communal dissensions.
</P>
<P>
"These attempts, however, will never bear fruit because Muslims
and Copts alike are aware that they are in the same boat," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Copts, which make up about 10 percent of the overwhelmingly
Muslim country of 63 million, have been the target of Muslim
militants attacks.
</P>
<P>
The president also urged journalists and writers to steer clear
of playing on "sham differences between Muslims and Copts."
</P>
<P>
"Both Muslims and Copts have been governed by the principle
which guides our national action since 1919, namely that religion
be devoted to good while Egypt be the homeland of both Muslims and
Copts, who are the elements of the one nation," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
He also paid tribute to Muslims and Copts alike for helping in
the fight against terrorism and maintaining the country's national
unity.
</P>
<P>
"The Copts are an inseparable part of Egypt and their rights as
Egyptians are fully protected," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since February, about 20 Copts have been killed in Muslim
militant attacks in southern Egypt. The latest attacks on
Christians a week ago brought to 1,169 the number of people
killed, since Muslim militants declared war on the government of
Hosni Mubarak in March 1992.
</P>
<P>
The government has vowed to strike hard at terrorism in the event
of the February 13 church attack, in which nine Copts were killed
and 6 others injured when gunmen opened fire in a Coptic church in
Minya, 240 kilometers south of Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
