<HEADLINE> China Hopes Foreign Correspondents Follow News Coverage Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China hopes that foreign
correspondents will follow the relevant Chinese regulations when
doing their news coverage and reporting in China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cui Tiankai made the remark
when asked to confirm and comment that Juergen Kremb, a
correspondent of the German weekly magazine, Der Speigel, was
detained by the police in Anhui during his reporting activities.
</P>
<P>
Cui said that on April 26, Juergen Kremb, a correspondent based
in Beijing, was found carrying out unauthorized news reporting in
Anhui without the prior application to and approval from the
Provincial Foreign Affairs Office. His action was in violation of
China's Regulations on the Supervision of Foreign Journalists and
Resident Foreign News Organs, Cui added.
</P>
<P>
The relevant local department interrogated him according to
law, criticized his wrongdoings, and asked him to abide by the
Chinese laws and regulations and explain to the relevant
department after his return to Beijing, Cui noted.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the foreign correspondents, including those from
Germany, to carry out news coverage and reporting in China," said
Cui, adding that in recent years, the number of foreign
correspondents visiting China keeps growing, and the Chinese side
has given these correspondents many conveniences for which they
have expressed their satisfaction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
