<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Working Class, Strong Driving Force for Reform: Editorial (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- People's Daily, China's leading
newspaper, will carry an editorial called "Deepening Reform and
the Working Class" tomorrow to mark International Workers' Day.
</P>
<P>
The editorial first extends warm congratulations and greetings
to workers, farmers, intellectuals of different ethnic groups, and
all the working people around the country, and greetings to
compatriots in Taiwan, Hong Kong, Macao, and overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The editorial says that China made a good beginning last year
for its Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), marked by the
achievement of an economic "soft landing" with curbed inflation
and sustained economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"With reform becoming an irreversible trend in socialist
China," it says, "the working class, as the masters of the country,
are leading the trend as the main force in, as well as a strong
driving force for the reform."
</P>
<P>
After 19 years of experimentation and exploration, the
editorial points out, reform and opening up have begun a period of
smooth development, presenting bright prospects for building
socialism with Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
And people's understanding, especially that of the working
class, of reform gets deeper, and their confidence rises, it says,
adding that "sublimation of the understanding is becoming a
tremendous material force to propel the deepening of the reform."
</P>
<P>
Reform of state-owned enterprises is key to accelerating the
two fundamental changes of the economic system and the economic
growth mode, the editorial notes, adding that it is inevitable
that they should encounter some difficulties during the process of
the reform of the economic system and readjustment of the
industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
It stresses that reform of state-owned enterprises is a major
strategic task in the reform of the economic system, and there is
no return.
</P>
<P>
"The difficulties in the reform process can only be overcome by
deepening the reform," says the editorial.
</P>
<P>
It elaborates that the deep-rooted problems for state-owned
enterprises that accumulated over the years have been fully
exposed, and "it is high time to address these problems;" while
the great achievements of reform and opening up and the sustained,
rapid, and healthy development of the national economy has created
rare opportunities for the reform of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Working Class, Strong Driving Force for Reform: Editorial (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The guiding principle of "giving full play to the role of Party
organizations in enterprises as the political core, adhering to
and perfecting the system in which factory directors or managers
take full responsibility of running the enterprises, and relying
on the working class whole-heartedly" must be implemented in reform
of state-owned businesses, the editorial points out.
</P>
<P>
Reliance on the working class have been the consistent policy of
the Party, and an important part of Deng Xiaoping's theory on
building socialism with Chinese characteristics, it says.
</P>
<P>
When China started reform and opening up 19 years ago, the
editorial says, Deng Xiaoping pointed out that the working class
were bound to play a pioneering role in these reforms for the
benefits of socialism and China's modernization, and their
association with mass production has decisively shown their high
political consciousness and strict discipline and that they can
play a leading role in economic development and social and
political progress.
</P>
<P>
"We should implement the policy of relying on the working class
whole-heartedly in the whole process of reform and opening up,"
the editorial emphasizes.
</P>
<P>
It notes that relying on the working class is consistent with
showing concern for them, since the goal of reform is common
prosperity, and facts have shown that everybody is the beneficiary
of the reform sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that some enterprise employees' interests might be
affected temporarily in the reform due to adjustment of the
economic structure and new distribution of interests, the
editorial calls for a correct understanding of the temporary
difficulties in terms of the long-term benefits.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, it points out that help should be rendered
to redundant and laid-off workers of state-owned enterprises by
carrying out reemployment projects, to reach the goal of good
livelihood of the working class and all the working people.
</P>
<P>
The editorial concludes that the working class, as the masters of
the country, will play even better their role as the main force in
the reform so as to carry forward the cause of building socialism
with Chinese characteristics, which was initiated by Deng
Xiaoping.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
