<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dubai's Trade Volume Soars in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The total trade volume of
Dubai, one of the seven emirates of the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), rose to 18.6 billion U.S. dollars in the first 10 months
of 1996, a 16.4 percent increase over the same period of 1995, an
economic report said here today.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same period in 1995, Dubai's imports rose by
15.2 percent to reach 14 billion dollars in January-October period
in 1996, while exports declined by 8.7 percent to stand at 960
million dollars and re-export trade soared by 31.2 percent to
reach 3.6 billion dollars, according to the report by the Studies
and Planning Division of the Dubai Department of Economic
Development.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the imports of durable consumer goods
stood at 6 billion dollars, accounting for 42.9 percent of the
total imports during the 1996's 10-month period.
</P>
<P>
The imports of foodstuff valued at 1.5 billion dollars,
accounting for 10.7 percent of the imports while capital goods
worth 4.87 billion dollars represented 34.7 percent of the total,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the top supplier to Dubai during the
first ten months of last year with its exports to Dubai reaching
1.61 billion dollars. It was followed by China, Japan, India,
South Korea, Britain, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Dubai's imports from the U.S. mainly included vehicles and
machinery while imports from China comprised mostly textiles,
textile products, electrical and mechanical equipment and
machinery, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Dubai's exports, the reports said that durable
consumer goods such as base metals and article of base metals
consisted of the main exports of Dubai, a trade and
distribution hub in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of last year, these goods valued at 770
million dollars were exported, accounting for 80 percent of the
total 960-million-dollar exports, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Japan ranked as Dubai's first export destination with a value
of 143 million dollars, followed by India, South Korea,
Britain, the U.S., Switzerland, Oman, Thailand and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Iran maintained its position as Dubai's top re-export
destination with exports amounting to 660 million
dollars. Machinery, electric and electronics products comprised
the main re-export items to Iran.
</P>
<P>
India was the second re-export destination among Dubai's 171
re-export places in the world with shipments valued at 271.5
million dollars. Pearls, precious stones and metals were the
major re-export items.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia came third with re-exports from Dubai amounting
to 184.7 million dollars, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Macao to Start New Air Route to Central China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Air Macao will start a regular new
air route to Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei province, as
of May 3, the air company has announced.
</P>
<P>
The new route will have three flights a week, that is on
Monday, Wednesday and Saturday. The aircraft will take off at
13:05 at the Macao International Airport and land in Wuhan at
14:45, according to a press release received today.
</P>
<P>
The plane will return the same afternoon, and back to Macao at
17:30, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
Air Macao's sixth aircraft, Airbus A321, arrived last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
After the inauguration of the new air route, Air Macao will
have 94 regular flights a week to cities including  Beijing,
Qingdao, Shanghai, Wuhan, Xiamen, Taipei, Kaohsiung and Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Founded in September 1994, Air Macao carried 662,000 passengers
 last year following the inauguration of the Macao International
Airport in November 1995, a better performance than expected, the
air company authorities said.
</P>
<P>
It plans to add air routes to Japan and some Southeast Asian
nations in the near future. Its fleet is expected to increase to
12 by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
