<HEADLINE> UK's Labor Leader Makes Final Appeal to Voters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition Labor leader
Tony Blair made a final appeal today to British voters to vote for
him and "vote for a change" in Thursday's election.
</P>
<P>
"We will not stop trying to persuade people to put their trust
in Labor. Between now and when the polls close tomorrow night we
will strive for every vote, in every corner of the country," he
told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
But the labor leader, who seems set to topple Conservatives'
18-year rule in line with opinion polls, warned once more against
complacency when the polling day is approaching.
</P>
<P>
"Because this election is not going to be decided by opinion
polls. It is not going to be resolved by pundits. It is in the
hands of the British people. Their future is in their hands," the
43-year-old Labor leader said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Blair sent out nearly 200 former Labor MPs out of
their own constituencies to the marginals that would decide
Thursday's election.
</P>
<P>
"If people think that Britain could be better they should vote
for a new and modern Labor party," he said. "So I ask the British
people for their support," he added.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls suggest the Labor party, which Blair has dragged
into the center of the political spectrum since taking charge
three years ago, is set to win by a landslide.
</P>
<P>
Today's Daily Telegraph newspaper published its last opinion
poll before the election, showing the Labor a 20-point lead
against the Conservatives with a projected majority of 203 seats
in the 659-seat House of Commons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
