<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Candidate Joins Liberia's Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Ellen Sirleaf, Liberia's former
female finance minister, has resigned her post of director for
the Africa region of the United Nations Development Program to
join the presidential election race scheduled for May 30.
</P>
<P>
The only female candidate, who will contest the presidential
poll as candidate of the Liberia Action Party, has tremendous
support from the female population which constitutes about 60
percent of the Liberian voters, a report reaching here said
today.
</P>
<P>
Sirleaf gained international attention in 1985 when late
Liberian President Samuel Doe jailed her for making what he
called derogatory statements about him.
</P>
<P>
She is therefore considered as the candidate who could most
easily gather the support of the international community behind
the monumental task of rebuilding Liberia.
</P>
<P>
However, Sirleaf will also face formidable opponents. Among
them are Charles Taylor, Alhaji Kromah and George Boley, former
leaders of the major three warring factions in the west African
country.
</P>
<P>
Other major presidential candidates include Cletus Waterson
representing a seven-party alliance, Togbanah Tiptoeh, former
planning minister under the Doe administration, and Gabriel
Matthews and Boina Fahnbulleh, former foreign affairs ministers.
</P>
<P>
As preparations are under way for the May 30 polls, lack of
funds is hampering the job of the Independent Electoral
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The commission has sent a detailed estimate of 12 million U.S.
Dollars to General Sani Abacha, Nigeria's head of state who is
also chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) and the ECOWAS Committee of Nine on Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The commission emphasized that the country would not be able
to source the funds necessary for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday, Abacha sent his foreign minister, Tom Ikimi, and
an ECOWAS delegation to Liberia to assess the preparations
for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The result of the one-week assessment tour is not yet known.
But diplomats said the Committee of Nine is unwilling to consider
any proposal to alter the transition timetable with a view to
shifting the elections date to later in the year.
</P>
<P>
However, how to raise funds for the forthcoming elections
remains a problem for Liberia's peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
