<HEADLINE> Colombian President to Visit S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President Ernesto
Samper Pizano is to pay a two-day official visit to South Africa
later this week at the invitation of President Nelson Mandela,
South Africa's Department of Foreign Affairs announced today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Pretoria, the department said Pizano
will hold discussions with Mandela about issues relating to the
Non-Aligned Movement (NAM).
</P>
<P>
"This visit will be of particular significance for South
Africa since Colombia is the current chair of the NAM," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
At a NAM's ministerial meeting held in India early this month,
South Africa was chosen as the host country for the NAM's 12th
summit of heads of state next year, at which it will take the
chairmanship of the NAM from Colombia.
</P>
<P>
NAM, established in 1961, is aimed to pursue goals crucial to
the needs of developing states and for the achievement of a more
stable, equitable and humane global dispensation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
