<HEADLINE> Zairean Peace Talks Still on Track: Says S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
Foreign Affairs Minister Aziz Pahad today confirmed that the
long-awaited peace talks between Zairean President Mobutu Sese
Seko and rebel leader Laurent Kabila would still be held on a
South African Navy ship later this week as originally proposed.
</P>
<P>
Pahad made the remarks in a response to reports from Zaire
claiming that Mobutu had objected to using a South African Navy
ship as venue for his first face-to-face talks with Kabila.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the South African Broadcasting
Corporation Radio, Pahad said as far as his government was
concerned, Mobutu and Kabila had earlier agreed to meet on the
navy ship, which would be anchored in international waters off
the coast of Zaire and Angola.
</P>
<P>
The only issues that had to be sorted out is related to
logistics and security, said Pahad, adding his government would
urge both parties "not to hesitated and to move very quickly to
the negotiating table."
</P>
<P>
Both United States special envoy Bill Richardson and United
Nations Special Envoy Mohamed Sahnoun are expected in Zairean
capital Kinshasa, the last major city held by soldiers loyal to
President Mobutu, later today to salvage the peace talks, which
would be chaired by South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
</TEXT>
