<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Industrialist Describes Trip to Iraq as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Jacques Sarraf, chairman of the
Lebanese Industrialists Association, described today the trip by a
group of Lebanese businessmen to Iraq last week as "very fruitful."
</P>
<P>
Sarraf and his ten-men delegation of leading business figures
from Lebanon's oil, food and clothing sectors returned home from
the week-long trip to the Iraqi capital Baghdad at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published here today, Sarraf said that the
Lebanese industrialist delegation had meetings with the Iraqi
ministers of health, trade, industry and minister of foreign
affairs.
</P>
<P>
"We met their chamber of commerce and the union of
industrialists. We also signed several protocols." he said in the
interview with the Daily Star, the only English daily in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that he preferred not to reveal details of
the visit before he met Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz,
who is due to return from a visit in Tunisia later this week.
</P>
<P>
Iraq used to be one of Lebanon's leading trade partners. But
their ties soured after the Iraqi government of Saddam Hussein
provided moral and material support for Michael Aoun, the former
Lebanese army general, in the military confrontations with
Lebanese Muslim factions backed by Syria's 35,000-strong forces
in Lebanon during 1989 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon severed its diplomatic relations with Iraq following
the 1994 assassination of Talib Suhgeil Al-Tamimi, a prominent
Iraqi dissenter, in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese judicial authorities arrested three Iraqi diplomats
shortly after the murder. But they were freed in January
reportedly at the request of the Lebanese foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Sarraf said in February that his Industrialists' Association
secured the release of the diplomats after persuading Boueiz into
improving trade links with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by the Lebanese industrialists to renew their ties
with Iraq came despite a U.N. embargo on Iraq in the wake of
its August 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the U.N. decided to ease the sanctions on Iraq
and allowed Baghdad to sell two-billion-dollar worth of oil over
a period of six months in exchange for food, medicines and
humanitarian supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
