<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khamenei Rejects German Envoy to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Supreme Leader Ali
Khamenei today ordered the Foreign Ministry not to allow the
German ambassador to Tehran to return for a period of time.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei also instructed the Foreign Ministry not to rush
in sending back Iranian ambassadors to their respective countries
of mission in the EU member states.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leader made the response one day after the EU
member states decided to send back their ambassadors to Tehran
at the ministerial meeting in Luxembourg Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
EU member states recalled their envoys from Tehran for
"consultations" following the ruling of the Berlin court on
April 10, which implicated top Iranian leaders behind the
assassination of the four exiled Kurdish opposition leaders in
Mykonos restaurant on September 17, 1992.
</P>
<P>
EU also decided to suspend ministerial level contact with
Iran and "critical dialog" with Tehran. However, it did not
adopt any economic sanction against Iran.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei described western governments as "unfair, ill-intentioned,
shameless and brazen because of their baseless accusations against
the Iranian nation and other nations of the world."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a group of teachers and workers who had called
on him on the occasion of the Teachers' and Workers' Day,
the Ayatollah strongly condemned western governments "for their
aggression against the rights of human beings in the last
one hundred years."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati declared here today that
some European ambassadors, especially German and Danish ambassadors,
are unwelcome in his country.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said at a press conference that Iran will response
the European countries with same the intensity but in opposite
direction. The loser would not be Iran but the Europeans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
