<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Textile Exports to Benefit from U.S. New Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Trade Development
Council (TDC) said today that the United States' planned
elimination of the single-entry bond requirement will benefit Hong
Kong's textile exports.
</P>
<P>
The single-entry bond requirement, which was imposed by the
U.S. last
June on selected Hong Kong textile exports, will be eliminated at
the end of today, TDC said in its latest Trade Watch report.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the step was purportedly taken to address
the problem of alleged illegal transshipments.
</P>
<P>
Under the old policy, Hong Kong exports of textile products in
those few selected categories must comply with additional
documentation requirements and be accompanied by single-entry
bonds in order to clear U.S. Customs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the U.S. importers had to provide to U.S. Customs
an original textile declaration signed by the importer declaring
that the textile declaration was accurate.
</P>
<P>
As a result, TDC said, Hong Kong's overall textile and apparel
exports to the U.S. declined 4 percent in 1996, a drop attributed
in part to the imposition of the single entry bond system.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hong Kong's domestic exports of seven of the eight
selected categories failed to achieve the same quota utilization
level they did in 1995, TDC added.
</P>
<P>
After a series of discussions between Hong Kong and U.S. trade
officials, the U.S. Customs Service announced early this month
that effective on May 1, 1997, it would no longer require
single-entry bonds on selected categories of Hong Kong textile
exports.
</P>
<P>
However, TDC noted that the retention of a modified version of
the additional documentation requirements, as well as their
extension to all textile categories, may continue to adversely
affect Hong Kong textile manufacturers and exporters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
