<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Agrees to Hold Inter-Korean Red Cross Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean National Red Cross
(KNRC) today informed its counterpart of the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) that it agreed to hold an inter-Korean
Red Cross meeting in Beijing to discuss aid delivery issues.
</P>
<P>
KNRC Chairman Kang Young-hoon conveyed his new position
to his counterpart Li Song-ho in Pyongyang through the
direct phone in the inter-Korean Red Cross liaison office in the
truce village of Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
Kang initiated a proposal on April 18 to hold high-level
representative talks in Panmunjom before he proposed working-level
contacts at the same place six days later.
</P>
<P>
But Li twice turned down the suggestions and counterproposed
Beijing as the venue for the meeting on May 3 without a
working-level contact.
</P>
<P>
Li Song-ho said that the two sides could meet in Beijing
"without any feeling burden."
</P>
<P>
Considering the food shortage in the DPRK, Seoul gave up its
principle of "inter-Korean dialogue inside the Peninsula" and
decided to accept Li's proposal "as an exception," KNRC officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, if happens, will be the first inter-Korean Red
Cross contact after a working-level meeting between the two
organizations was suspended in August 1992.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will send a six-member delegation led by the KNRC
general secretary to Beijing for the meeting, while the site and
date of the meeting would be decided through phone contact between
the two Red Cross societies, Kang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Becomes World's Largest Ceramics Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China was listed as the world's
largest architectural and sanitary ceramics producer at the
international symposium on ceramics which recently concluded in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
China produced 1.584 billion sq m of architectural ceramics and
55 million units of sanitary ceramics in 1996, ranking first in
the world, according to Wu Bin, executive vice-president of the
Building Materials Chamber of Commerce under the China Chamber of
International Commerce (CCOIC).
</P>
<P>
The official said that over ten years, China has developed more
than 800 large and medium-sized architectural and sanitary
ceramics enterprises as well as thousands of township-run
enterprises. The cities of Foshan, Tangshan, and Boshan have
become the country's largest ceramics production bases.
</P>
<P>
Wu noted that the booming building sector has provided great
opportunities for the development of architectural and sanitary
ceramics production.
</P>
<P>
Presently, the country's annual urban and rural housing
construction averages at 300 million sq m and 600 million sq m,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, China is projected to add 230 new cities and
5,000 towns, which will create huge market for the architectural
and sanitary ceramics products.
</P>
<P>
Widespread Sino-foreign cooperation and technological exchanges
have boosted the upgrading of technology and equipment in the
ceramics sector, according to Liu Jingzhou, senior engineer of the
Building Materials Sub-Council of the China Council for the
Promotion of International Trade.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that more than 440 ceramics businesses have introduced
complete production lines from abroad, including more than 2,000
automatic ceramics press machines introduced from Italy, Germany,
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
An official source expects China to maintain its status as the
world's largest architectural and ceramics producer until the year
of 2010.
</P>
<P>
The source added that the State Administration of Building
Materials Industry and the China Council for the Promotion of
International Trade will co-sponsor the International Ceramics
Exhibition scheduled to be held in Guangzhou between May 12 and 16.
</P>
<P>
And over 150 ceramics enterprises from Italy, Germany, Japan,
Britain, France, the United States, Russia, and China will display
their latest ceramics products, technology, and equipment at the
exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
