<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Hospital Staff to Wage Strike Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Hospital staff throughout Lebanon
will go on strike Friday in face of their dire financial woes
largely caused by unpaid bills, the Lebanese Hospitals' Syndicate
announced in a statement published this morning.
</P>
<P>
Public and private hospitals will handle only emergency cases
during a day-long stoppage, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"All institutions, governmental and private, owe us money and
all we receive are promises," Faouzi Adaimi, head of the syndicate
told a press conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The sum owed by the government and private sector since 1995
stands at 500 billion Lebanese pounds (324.7 million
U.S. dollars)," Adaimi said.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the government in setting a low budget share -- some
3 percent -- for health care and for the delays in payment for the
situation.
</P>
<P>
The syndicate chief said that the government's budget failed to
take into account the increase in population and a rising cost of
health care.
</P>
<P>
About one tenth of the country's 4 million population receive
hospital treatment each year, Adaimi said, noting 300,000 people's
medical fare is covered by the government or army.
</P>
<P>
He added most hospitals are unable to pay salaries on time and
some are not even able to pay the monthly wages at all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
