<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Meets Japanese Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China-Japan relations are in an
important period of inheriting the past and ushering in the
future, Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the Central Committee of
the Communist Party of China (CPC), said here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks in a meeting with a delegation of the
Liberal Democratic Party of Japan led by Yamazaki Taku, chairman
of the party's Political Affairs Investigation Committee.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations and the 20th anniversary of the
signing of the China-Japan Treaty of Peace and Friendship.
</P>
<P>
Extending a warm welcome to the Japanese visitors, Jiang said
that relations are now in a significant period that serves as a
link between the past and the future.
</P>
<P>
"To stick to the China-Japan Joint Declaration and the
China-Japan Treaty of Peace and Friendship is an important
guarantee to push forward the bilateral relations in a healthy and
steady way," he said, adding "It is also an important guarantee to
maintain the two peoples' friendship from generation to
generation."
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that in the past 25 years, the Sino-Japanese ties
have yielded profound development in all fields through the
unremitting efforts of the two governments and the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
As the world draws near the 21st century, the Chinese president
said, the two sides, leaders in particular, should take a
comprehensive and far-sighted view of the entire bilateral
relationship, and deal with emerging problems in a sober-minded
and proper way to make the future relations progress in a more
healthy and smooth manner.
</P>
<P>
Yamazaki Taku said his delegation is here hoping to promote the
bilateral friendly relations. It appreciated the great
achievements China has scored in its reform and opening up after
having seen them with their own eyes, he said.
</P>
<P>
China's progress is conducive to that of Asia and the Pacific
and the world at large, he said, adding Japan, as China's close
neighbor separated only by a strip of water, is willing to join
China to continue the bilateral good-neighborly ties with the
understanding that "the past experience, if not forgotten, should
serve as a guide for the future".
</P>
<P>
This will help contribute to peace in the Asia-Pacific region
and the world at large, he added.
</P>
<P>
Li Shuzheng, head of the International Department of the CPC
Central Committee, and Yashiyasu Sato, Japanese ambassador to
China, attended today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Yamazaki Taku and his party arrived here Sunday as guests of
the CPC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
