<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toward A China-U.S. Relationship for the 21st Century: Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The current social and economic systems in Hong Kong will
remain unchanged, and so will its way of life. The laws in Hong
Kong will remain basically unchanged. Hong Kong will retain its
status as a free port, a separate customs territory and an
international financial center. The Hong Kong dollar will continue
to be used and peg on the U.S. dollar. The central government of
China will not collect a single Hong Kong dollar in taxes from
Hong Kong. The government of the Hong Kong SAR will be composed
entirely of local inhabitants and the central government will not
send any officials to Hong Kong. Foreign economic interest in Hong
Kong will be protected.
</P>
<P>
Concerns have been expressed overseas that Hong Kong's
democracy, human rights and press freedom will be restricted in
the future. What will actually happen in Hong Kong, however, is
that after its return, the democracy, freedoms and human rights
enjoyed by the Hong Kong people will be more extensive. They will
be increased rather than decreased. Many such rights are beyond
the reach of the Hong Kong people under the British rule. The
central government will only be responsible for Hong Kong's
defense and foreign affairs. The departments of central government
will not interfere in matters which fall under the authority of
the Hong Kong SAR which enjoys a high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The success in implementing the principle of "one country, two
systems" will ensure Hong Kong's stability and prosperity. It is
not only in the interests of Hong Kong and China, but also the
interests of other countries and regions, including the United
States, that have extensive economic and trade links with Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 25th anniversary of the Shanghai
Communique. Twenty-five years ago, with courage and statesmanship,
Chinese and American leaders reopened the relationship between our
two countries. Today, after twenty-five years,
China-U.S. relationship is once again faced with a historic
opportunity for improvement and growth. We should once again show
strategic vision and courage, just as our leaders did in those
days, remove interferences and obstacles, and press forward
towards our goal. Thus, when the next century arrives, we will
have a sound, stable and steadily growing relationship between our
two countries which benefits not just our two peoples but the
people of the whole world. Let us join hands and work for the
establishment of such a relationship geared to the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to End Power Rationing Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The seven-month electricity
rationing in Kenya is expected to be over after heavy rains
improved water levels in main supply stations.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Power and Lighting Company (KPLC) said owing to the
heavy rains, the water levels of Seven Forks and Turkwel dams had
gone up, allowing for stepped-up hydro-generation.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by KPLC noted that the water levels at the
Seven Forks and Turkwel dams had risen by seven meters since the
rains started about four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
KPLC spokesman Mike Njeru said on Tuesday that heavy rains had
helped KPLC step up generation by around 40 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
According to Njeru, five of the eight power units for the
Nairobi South Power Station imported from Britain are already in
Nairobi and the first unit will produce power in June.
</P>
<P>
The diesel-power Nairobi South Power Station will contribute
44.5 megawatts for national consumption.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a barge-mounted thermal plant supplied by Malaysian
company Westmont off the southern port of Mombasa is expected to
be ready in June.
</P>
<P>
On March 9, former Energy Minister Kirugi M'Mukindia said the
power rationing, which started last September, would come to an
end when the 43-megawatts barge power plant and 44.5-megawatts
diesel power plant in Nairobi started operating.
</P>
<P>
The installed power capacity in Kenya is 784 megawatts with an
additional 30 megawatts imported from neighboring Uganda while
the actual power generating capacity oscillates between 570 and
650 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The deficiency is blamed mainly on poor weather, poor
maintenance and constant breakdowns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
