<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Strike Hard" Campaign Making China Safer (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China's "strike hard" campaign,
which started a year ago, has brought the country's crime rate
down for the first time in many years, Bai Jingfu, vice-minister
of public security, said here today.
</P>
<P>
The campaign included the "joint mission", "winter mission",
and the present "spring rectification mission". Thanks to these
actions and participation by the whole society, China's public
order has taken a turn for the better, Bei said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Public Security Ministry, the number of crimes
investigated by police in the first two months of last year was
12.6 percent higher than for the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The crime rate for all of 1996 dropped 5.4 percent, and that
for the first two months of this year was down 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by Beijing's police bureau, 90 percent of
the people say that public order has improved since the
crackdown. Legislators in the National People's Congress Standing
Committee discovered, during a recent tour, that the public feel
"much safer".
</P>
<P>
China has continued its intensified anti-crime drive since
1983, but this round, unlike the earlier ones, was started by the
Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party and supported by
party committees, governments at various levels, and the rest of
society.
</P>
<P>
Police and prosecutors, with sufficient help from the
government, have worked harder, increased their efficiency, and
given harsher speedier sentences on criminals in accordance with
the law.
</P>
<P>
Bai noted that a striking feature of this anti-crime fight has
been the rigorous compliance with the law, and that "no matter how
harsh or how quick the sentence, they are always within the limits
of the law."
</P>
<P>
China's laws provide sufficient legal guarantees for the
"strike hard" drive, which protects citizens from being infringed
upon by law enforcers, said Gao Mingxuan, a law professor and
executive director of the China Law Society's Criminal Law Chapter.
</P>
<P>
As for the burdens the drive places on the policemen, Guo Benli
at the Changqiao Substation in Beijing, said, "We just don't have
a day off even on weekends, and some of the men can't even find
time to see their wives if they're sick."
</P>
<P>
But, it was precisely because of this hard work that a large
number of the serious cases were solved, including a notorious
armed robbery of bank vehicles in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
A large amount of potential losses to both the state and the
people has been recovered, causing potential wrongdoers to think
twice, and effectively stopping a great deal of vice, Bai said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Strike Hard" Campaign Making China Safer (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The public are enthusiastic about the anti-crime
work. According to statistics, during the crackdown, more than 80
percent of the crimes were revealed by leads from the public, and
45 percent of the criminals were apprehended with their help.
</P>
<P>
"The massive public participation means a gigantic camouflaged
police force for China, who have played a vital role in the
anti-crime fight," Bai explained.
</P>
<P>
"'Strike hard' is more our business than the government's," Ma
Hongguan, who is a self-employed key maker and who once helped
police catch a thief, wrote in the public opinion section of a
Beijing "Strike Hard" Achievement Exhibition last year. The
exhibition drew more than 170,000 visitors, including many foreign
journalists.
</P>
<P>
Professor Gao attributed the comprehensive management system to
the "strike hard" campaigns. China is setting up a nationwide
crime prevention system and rapid reaction mechanism with police
linked to communities.
</P>
<P>
The Public Security Ministry has repeatedly said that in spite
of the success of this fight, China still faces a serious public
security situation.
</P>
<P>
Some hardened criminals are defying the crackdown and public
security problems in some places have not been rooted out, the
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang Haibo, a researcher at the China Academy of
Social Sciences, China will have a hard and long time to return to
the age when people didn't have to lock their doors at night. But,
he adds, "With an effective crime prevention system and the
continuing 'strike hard' actions, the public will still be
guaranteed of their safety, and China will remain one of the
countries with the lowest crime rate in the world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
