<HEADLINE> Tensions Rise in S. Lebanon as International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Tensions shrouds south Lebanon
following a fresh round of exchanging fire between Israeli
forces and Lebanese guerrillas as cease-fire monitors continued a
meeting today to discuss Israeli and Lebanese protests.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese security sources said that the Israeli forces at
positions in a the security strip the Jewish state occupies in
south Lebanon bombarded a number of targets in the areas of
Nabatiyeh and Iglim Al-Toffah over last night.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli forces at Dabshe and Sweida swept vicinities of
their positions with heavy machinegun fire, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Israeli artillery also shelled Nabatiyeh Fauqa, Habboush and
the Litani river basin in the central and western sectors of
south Lebanon on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese pro-Iranian guerrilla, Hezbollah, or Party of
God, announced that its fighters launched a series of attacks at
the Israeli outposts of Kasarat Aroush, Dabshe, Sweida and
Sejoud "with various weapons" at midnight.
</P>
<P>
As-Safir, a leftist daily published in Beirut, reported this
morning that Hezbollah fired Sam-7 missiles and other anti-air
weapons toward Israeli jet fighters carrying out reconnaissance
missions over Western Beqaa Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli warplanes released hot balloons to avert the
upward ground fire, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire monitoring committee adjourned Tuesday evening
an inconclusive debate on two complaints presented by Lebanon
and Israel over violations of the year-old truce agreement
against involving civilians in military operations in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the five-member monitoring committee,
grouping France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States
met for seven hours in the headquarters of the U.N. peacekeeping
force at the south Lebanese border town of Naqoura to listen to
the Israeli complaint about an cross-border attack by Hezbollah
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israel said two Israeli soldiers were wounded when two mortar
shells landed at an army base on the Israeli side of the
Lebanese-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
The committee will meet again at 11:00 a.m. (08:00 GMT) today
to review a separate petition by Lebanon over Sunday's attack on
a school bus packed with children.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon said the bus was hit by six 12.7-mm bullets fired
from a hilltop position held by Israeli troops and the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia in the occupied border
zone.
</P>
<P>
None of the children were hurt, but the attack traumatized
the children, aged between four and 12, who were on their way to
school run by the Shiite fundamentalist Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Under the April 26 cease-fire understanding, which ended a
17-day Israeli blitz against Lebanon last year, Israel and
Lebanese guerrillas are barred from targeting civilians or
launching attacks from civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese guerrillas are also prohibited from opening fire
across the border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
