<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Language Keeps Pace with Computer Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Computer researchers in southwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region have worked out standard coding of
the Tibetan language to keep pace with the information age.
</P>
<P>
"Coding the Tibetan language enables us to directly get access
to computer information and networks," said Nyima Cering with the
Tibet University, who heads a team of computer experts in the
research of coding Tibetan language.
</P>
<P>
The team began their work in 1994, and after three years of
arduous work, their coding standard has been accepted by world
computer organizations, including Microsoft in the United States.
</P>
<P>
With the assistance of this coding interface, computer users of
Tibetan language will be able to use the software developed by
many computer companies in the world, Nyima Cering said.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with international coding standards, the experts
have also won approval from the State Bureau of Technological
Supervision for their coding of Tibetan characters, keyboards, and
fonts.
</P>
<P>
"On this basis, we will develop application software in Tibetan
language to make the information network serve the development of
the Tibetan language," Nyima Cering said.
</P>
<P>
With the improvement of information technology, computer
typesetting of Tibetan has taken the place of stereotyping, and
the diversified types of printing styles of Tibetan had to be
standardized, Nyima Cering said.
</P>
<P>
So far, 22 types of fonts have been approved by state
departments as standard Tibetan printing fonts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toward A China-U.S. Relationship for the 21st Century: Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China wishes to join the World Trade Organization. This serves
China's own interests as it will help deepen its reform and
opening up program. What is more, it meets the interest of the
United States and other trading partners of China. Recently,
progress was made in the latest round of negotiations between
China and the United States in Geneva. I hope the negotiating
teams of both countries will redouble their efforts to reach early
agreement through consultation on an equal footing. After all,
both the MFN treatment and the WTO should be mechanisms for
promoting world trade and cooperation among countries. They should
not be used as a tool to put political pressure on others.
</P>
<P>
We are living in a diverse world. China and the United States
differ in social system, historical background, cultural
tradition, values and level of economic development. It is
therefore not surprising that they have different views on human
rights. Some people in the United States take American standards
on human rights to judge if there is democracy in China. I don't
think this is the right way to go about it.
</P>
<P>
China has its own national conditions, just as the United
States does. Under China's democratic system, the Chinese people
enjoy extensive freedoms and human rights, although they are not
expressed the same way as in the United States. China's democracy
is the choice made by the Chinese people, just as yours is the
choice made by the American people.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government attaches great importance to promoting
human rights. In keeping with the principle of universality of
human rights and China's specific national conditions, it has made
great efforts to ensure the rights to survival and development for
the Chinese people. As a result, the Chinese people are enjoying
extensive economic, social and cultural rights. At the same time,
China has stepped up the building of democracy and legal system to
uphold the civil and political rights of its people.
</P>
<P>
China takes an active part in the U.N. efforts to promote and
protect human rights. It has become party to 17 international
human rights instruments, two more than the United States. China
has, on many occasions, spoken positively of the international
Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights and the
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. After
careful consideration, China has decided to first sign the
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights by
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
As for differences on human rights, it has all along been
China's position that they should be handled through dialogue and
exchange of views on the basis of equality and mutual
respect. Confrontation is not the right choice for addressing the
issue. Instead of solving the problem, it can only make things
more difficult and impair bilateral cooperation in other
areas. Since 1990, the Western countries have tried for seven
years to pass resolutions against China at the U.N. Human Rights
Commission in Geneva, but with no success. This shows that such a
practice is both unreasonable and unpopular.
</P>
<P>
Some people in the United States are concerned that China will
carry out arms proliferation and thus threaten American
security. Such concern is unfounded. The fact is that China has
consistently stood against arms proliferation. It has actively
participated in international disarmament activities and put
forward practical and effective disarmament proposals. China has
become party to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear
Weapons and the Biological Weapons Convention, and signed the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and the Chemical Weapons Convention.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with its international treaty obligations, China has
adopted and implemented corresponding steps on export-control, and
is constantly improving them. As for the export of conventional
weapons, China has all along taken a very prudent and responsible
approach towards it. China's arms export is very limited, taking
up only a very small share of the international arms market. It is
nothing compared with that of the United States, which chalks up
nearly 60 percent of the international arms sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Australian Wool Exporters Concerned About </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- A surge in wool prices over the
past month in Australia, which has lifted the eastern market
indicator to a 19-month high to 659 Australian cents (514 U.S.
cents) a kilogram, has led to concerns among the wool exporters.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator jumped another 19 Australian cents
per kilogram after auctions last week, bringing to 40 cents the
rise in the three weeks of selling since the Easter break.
</P>
<P>
And now it is at its highest level since September 1995 and
more than 100 Australian cents (78 U.S. cents) above the low to
which it sank eight months later.
</P>
<P>
Executive Director of the Australian Council of Wool Exporters
Bob Quirk said that the movement was long overdue news for
growers, but there were increasing reports of fabric and garment
manufacturers strongly resisting rises in the prices of raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
"This makes it very difficult for topmakers and spinners to
operate at profitable margins, which ultimately must have an
adverse effect on greasy wool prices," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The ideal situation," he thought, "would be to have continuous
but smaller increases in price from week to week."
</P>
<P>
Exporters said the market recovery was caused by competition
among local and overseas processors. In addition, a low offering
at auctions also contributed to the market moving up.
</P>
<P>
The wool stockpile is slowly declining, reportedly at 1.8
million bales. Last week, the Wool International sold about 28,000
bales, after selling 25,000 bales the week before.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toward A China-U.S. Relationship for the 21st Century: Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China and the United States share the same goal and a great
deal of common interests in preventing the proliferation of
weapons of mass destruction. In recent years, the two countries
have held useful dialogues on non-proliferation and reached some
common understanding in this regard. The Chinese side is ready to
maintain dialogue and consultation on this issue with the
U.S. side.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the issue of non-proliferation, what concerns us in
China most is the U.S. arms sales to Taiwan. Such arms sales
undermine China's sovereignty and pose a security threat to
China's mainland. They also work against peace and stability in
the Taiwan Straits. We hope that the U.S. government will
seriously address China's concern and strictly abide by the August
17 Joint Communique. It should reduce and halt its proliferation
of arms and related technologies to China's Taiwan region, so as
to create with concrete actions conditions for
China-U.S. cooperation in the field of non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
It should be pointed out that Taiwan is the single most
important and most sensitive issue in China-U.S. relations. It is
also the biggest obstacle to the sound growth of these
relations. Taiwan has been an inseparable part of China's
territory since ancient times. To end the state of separation
across the Taiwan Straits is the strong aspiration and unshakable
national will of the Chinese people, including the Taiwan
compatriots.
</P>
<P>
The formula of "peaceful reunification based on one country,
two systems" and the eight-point proposal made by President Jiang
Zemin on promoting China's peaceful reunification are both the
consistent policy and concrete plan of the Chinese government on
this question. At their very heart is the principle of one
China. It is the basis and premise of peaceful reunification. Not
only China, I don't think the government and people of any other
country can tolerate actions aimed at its division. The American
people have gone through their own Civil War. You should be able
to appreciate the Chinese people's firm desire for reunification
and their resolve against national separation.
</P>
<P>
On many occasions, the U.S. government leaders have reaffirmed
the continued U.S. commitment to the "one China" policy and to
the three China-U.S. Joint Communiques. It is our hope that
these commitments will be honored.
</P>
<P>
It should be pointed out that the Taiwan authorities are using
various means, including money, to split China and pursue
independence. We should stand on guard against such plot and make
sure that the Taiwan issue will not once again stand in the way of
better and closer relations between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
It is now only two months before the Chinese government resumes
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong. At present, Hong Kong is
enjoying sustained economic growth, growing public confidence and
an increasing flow of people returning from overseas. Both the
Hong Kong people and the international investors have great
confidence in Hong Kong. The preparations for the establishment of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) is progressing
smoothly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
