<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toward A China-U.S. Relationship for The 21st Century: Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen today made a speech at a luncheon
held in his honor by the Council on Foreign Relations, the
U.S.-China Business Council and the National Committee on
U.S.-China Relations.
</P>
<P>
The full text of the speech, which is entitled "Toward a
China-U.S. relationship for the 21st century," reads as follows.
</P>
<P>
Mr. President,
</P>
<P>
Ladies and Gentlemen,
</P>
<P>
I wish to thank the Council on Foreign Relations, the
U.S.-China Business Council and the National Committee on
U.S.-China Relations for their invitation. I also want to thank
you, Mr. President, for your kind and friendly introduction. It is
a great pleasure for me to meet the distinguished audience here
today. Please allow me to take this opportunity to speak on
China-U.S. relations and the Hong Kong question which, I
understand, is of interest to you.
</P>
<P>
As the new century is about to set in, our world is, on the
whole, moving towards greater relaxation. Working for peace,
development and cooperation has become the mainstream of
international life.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, there are still some uncertain and
destabilizing factors in the world. Troubles and conflicts keep
cropping up in some regions. The gap between the rich and poor
countries continues to widen. Cross-boundary crime, terrorism and
environmental damage are threatening and undermining the survival
and sustainable development of mankind.
</P>
<P>
What kind of a world should we bring into the 21st
century? This is the question facing each and every one of us.
</P>
<P>
Both China and the United States are permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council. Ours is the largest developing country and
yours is the largest developed country in the world.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, we share a common responsibility in maintaining
peace and stability in both Asia-Pacific and the rest of the
world. We also share important responsibility in promoting global
economic prosperity, improving human environment and many other
important matters. The need for both countries to stay engaged
with each other is increasing, not decreasing. The potential for
both countries to cooperate in various fields is expanding, not
dwindling. We should firmly bear these common interests in mind
and step up cooperation. We should also work together with other
countries to bring a peaceful, stable and prosperous world into
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
I am glad to see that China-U.S. relations have improved a lot
recently. High-level official exchanges have increased
steadily. Bilateral economic relations and trade are expanding.
Military-to-military exchanges have made headway. With support
from our leaders, the first meeting of China-U.S. Forum on
Environment and Development was successfully held in Beijing,
which opened a new field of cooperation between the two
countries. At present, both sides are making preparations for the
state visits to be exchanged between President Jiang Zemin and
President Clinton this year and next. China-U.S. relations have an
opportunity for further growth.
</P>
<P>
However, I must point out that while the relationship is making
progress, from time to time we still hear the sound of discord and
encounter interferences. For instance, some people in the United
States are spreading the "China threat" theory. According to
their argument, China has replaced the former Soviet Union as the
main threat to the United States. Others predict that China and
the United States will move towards confrontation, even conflict,
and therefore call for containment against China. There are also
people who liken today's China to Germany and Japan at the end of
the nineteenth and early twentieth century. They believe that as
its economy and national strength grow, China is bound to pursue
external expansion. These views, I must say, could not be more
wrong.
</P>
<P>
A review of China's history shows China does not have a
tradition of expansion. On the contrary, it was the victim of
repeated foreign aggression, domination and bullying. China has
never occupied a single inch of foreign soil, nor has it stationed
a singly soldier abroad.
</P>
<P>
Today's China is a developing country. What it desires most
is a peaceful international environment, so that it can focus on
economic development and improve the life of its 1.2 billion
people. Because of this, China has firmly adhered to an
independent foreign policy of peace and worked to maintain and
develop friendly relations and cooperation with other countries.
</P>
<P>
China's defense policy is completely defensive in nature. Its
defense spending is the lowest among the big countries in absolute
terms. In per capita terms as well as in terms of the share of the
GNP, it is among the lowest in the world. According to statistics,
the 1996 defense budget of the United States exceeded 260 billion
dollars, averaging 996 dollars per American. China's defense
spending was only 8.7 billion dollars and 7 dollars per
Chinese. Let these basic facts and figures speak for themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
