<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man in Zambia Jailed for Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- A 25-year-old young man has been
sentenced to three years of imprisonment with hard labor at a
Ndola magistrate's court in Zambia's Copperbelt province, charged
with abuse of the rare drug lysergide (LSD).
</P>
<P>
The accused W. Mushangaila induced the victim C. Gwamu to take
the drug and later stealing from him property and cash valued
about 300 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
This is the first case reported in the country involving the
abuse of LSD. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Towards A China-US Relationship for the 21st Century: Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From the viewpoint of development, China will still be a
developing country for a long time in the 21st century. It will
not be in a position to threaten anyone, nor will there be any
need for it to do so. Even if it becomes stronger in the future,
China will not pursue aggression and expansion, still less will it
seek hegemony. This, as a matter of principle, has been written
into China's Constitution.
</P>
<P>
China is not the former Soviet Union, nor is it the old-time
Germany or Japan. China is China. It will not follow the beaten
track of other countries. It seems that those people crying "China
threat" don't bother to study either history or reality. They are
only interested in finding a new "enemy" for the United States
after the collapse of the Soviet Union. Even if they can not find
one, they must create one, as if only by doing so can the United
States carry on as a superpower. This, in fact, is the revival of
the Cold War thinking under new conditions today. It is indeed
regrettable that such thinking has resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
Recently, there has been much media coverage about the
so-called "political contribution" made by China in the United
States. We have an old saying in China, "Just as you do not want
others to do things that hurt you, do not do the same thing to
them." In handling its relations with other countries, the Chinese
government has all along strictly observed the principle of
non-interference in each other's internal affairs. Just as China
is opposed to foreign interference in its internal affairs, it
definitely does not interfere in the internal affairs of other
countries. Having suffered greatly from foreign interference,
China does not in any way meddle in other countries' domestic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Sure, there are political contributions and money politics in
the United States. But they have nothing to do with China. Some
people make groundless charges against China and try to tarnish
its image. They just want to give vent to their opposition to the
improvement of China-U.S. relations. But I am confident that
China-U.S. relations are bound to go forward. Any attempt to
derail them by such low means will get nowhere.
</P>
<P>
Because there are imbalances in China-U.S. trade, some people
fear China will become "another Japan." Actually, China's trade
surplus with the United States has been greatly overstated. As for
the main cause for this issue, I think it is better to leave it to
the experts of the two countries to discuss. But I can say for
certain that China will not become "another Japan" in trade.
</P>
<P>
Japan is a highly developed and industrialized country.
Economically, it is very competitive. But China is a developing
country with a rather weak industrial base. Japan's export to the
United States is mainly made of high value-added,
technology-intensive products. As for China, it mainly exports low
value-added, labor-intensive products such as textiles, footwear
and toys to the United States. Especially such products like
footwear and toys are either no longer produced or produced only
in small amounts in the United States. Therefore, import from
China of such goods will not cost American jobs. Rather, it brings
about a lot of benefits to American consumers.
</P>
<P>
On its part, China imports from the United States a lot of high
technology products such as aircraft, machinery, electronic
products, telecommunication equipment and other products to meet
its urgent needs of economic development. Therefore, China-U.S.
economic and trade relationship is not one of competition. Rather,
it is a trading relationship in which the strong points of one
side complement the other side. In the foreseeable future, China's
economy will not pose any threat to the United States.
</P>
<P>
I am glad to note that China-U.S. economic cooperation and
trade have maintained good momentum of growth. In 1996, the United
States became China's No.2 trading partner, with total two-way
trade reaching 42.8 billion dollars. By the end of 1996, the
United States had invested in over 22,000 projects in China with a
total paid-in capital of 14.29 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
We welcome greater involvement by American businesses in
China's development program and their participation in competition
in China's market. This will fully tap the vast potential of
economic cooperation and trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
And I want to tell you this. As its economy grows, China will
open its market still wider and increase its import from the
United States. At the same time, we hope that the American
government will further liberalize its control over technology
export and credit lending to China, and remove all the man-made
hurdles that hinder the entry of American products into China's
market.
</P>
<P>
The current practice of reviewing China's MFN status annually
not only harms our bilateral economic relations and trade, but
also affects China-U.S. relations as a whole. The American
business community and more and more people with vision in the
United States are calling for a permanent solution to the MFN
issue, so as to base our economic and trade ties on a solid
foundation of long-term stability. I believe what they are doing
is sound and farsighted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Kills 44 Rebels in North, West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's government troops
killed 44 rebels in north and west of the country, local
newspaper the Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Ugandan government troops killed at least 14
rebels of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) in two separate
fightings in northern Gulu District.
</P>
<P>
The LRA, a rebel group acting in the north, sent a group into
Gulu city two weeks ago to try to launch terrorist activities
there. But now the situation is under control, according to a
spokesman of the government troops.
</P>
<P>
The government troops and security forces also killed at least
30 rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) in western Kasese
District on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The ADF is a rebel group acting in western Uganda and lost its
main forces in its fightings against the government troops late
last December and early in January. Its remaining forces have
divided into small groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
