<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia to Raise Government Employees' Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia decided to increase
the government employees' pay by 20 percent as from May 1, a press
report said today.
</P>
<P>
The pay fund in educational and medical units will go up by 25
percent, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia will have to pay 8.6 billion togrog (about 10.8
million U.S. dollars) more for this hike, Health and Social
Security Minister Lhagvajav Zorig told a news conference on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Up to 142,000 employees are paid by the government. The current
monthly pay for a common employee is 20,000 togrog (about 25
dollars) and that for a minister or a province governor is 40,000
togrog (about 50 dollars).
</P>
<P>
People began to go on the streets and asked for higher pay and
improved living standard since the end of last year because of the
decline of the country's economy in the second half of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian government has taken some measures, such as
canceling import duties, reducing taxes of enterprises and
increasing employees' pay, to help restore production, attract
more foreign investment and stablize prices and society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
