<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 29 -- The following are the major economic
news briefs from Latin America over past few days:
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian exports of software will reach 150
million U.S. dollars over the next 5 years, up 50 percent compared
with current amounts. The country's software exports in the
international market have increased since offices of the Softex
(Brazil) Company were opened abroad.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- While 2,106 informal industrial companies initiated
operations in Costa Rica during the 1990-1996 period, only 372
industrial companies did so legally, figures from the Chamber of
Industries of this Central American country showed.
</P>
<P>
This means that during that period, the rate of growth reached
50 percent for the former versus just 8.3 percent for the latter.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the General Statistics and Census
Department, more than 70,000 Costa Ricans or 50 percent of the
economically-active population engage in informal economic
activities.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina exported 322,436 tons of fresh citric
fruit last year which represented an increase of 25.3 percent over
the previous year to establish a new record in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock, Fisheries and Food
pointed out that this figure makes Argentina the 8th largest
exporter of citric fruits in the world after Brazil, the United
States, China, Mexico, Italy, Egypt and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The harvest for that period yielded 1,825,514 tons versus
2,098,650 tons harvested in the previous growning season.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Venezuelan government and the Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) signed a 14 million-dollar loan in
Washington which will serve to stabilize and fortify Venezuela's
financial system.
</P>
<P>
The loan was approved in 1995 and part of it has been exercised
through a technical group coordinated by Venezuela's central bank.
</P>
<P>
The program is part of an effort coordinated by the IDB, the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund to lend technical
assistance to Venezuelan authorities so that they can correct the
weakness in their regulating institutions as well as strengthen
them in the short and medium periods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Welcomes EU Decision on Easing Trade Curbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav Foreign Ministry
today welcomed the decision of the European Union (EU) on granting
Serbia trade preferences.
</P>
<P>
It said in a statement that the EU decision is a major step
toward promoting and developing comprehensive cooperation between
Yugoslavia and the EU.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Yugoslavia believes the time to
accelerate its all-around relations with the EU has come.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the EU's 15 member states decided
earlier today at a meeting in Luxembourg to ease trade
restrictions on Serbia.
</P>
<P>
The decision means that Yugoslavia will be allowed duty free
access and elimination of tariffs for the bulk of its industrial
products and some of its farm goods to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia exported 1.86 billion U.S. dollars' products to EU
member states last year. But because it did not enjoy special trade
privileges then, its foreign exchange earnings was reduced by 450
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations placed a trade embargo on Belgrade in 1992
after the Bosnian war broke out. It was lifted last October.
</P>
<P>
The EU planned to ease quotas and duties against Yugoslavia
last winter, but cancelled the move because of massive street
protests in Belgrade against the annulment of local elections in
November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
