<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank to Launch Debt Relief Plan for Poor Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank have agreed to launch a debt relief plan
for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
Uganda will be the first to benefit but will have to wait until
April of next year to have 700 million U.S. dollars or 20 percent
of its foreign debt to be written off, said a communique issued
today at the end of the 55th Ministerial meeting of the
Development Committee of the two financial bodies.
</P>
<P>
There is also a preliminary agreement on the eligibility of
three other countries -- Bolivia, Burkina Faso and Cote d'Ivoire
-- for the debt relief plan.
</P>
<P>
The communique said integration into the international trading
system and access to adequate external resource flows are
essential for the developing countries to reduce their poverty.
</P>
<P>
The Development Committee is scheduled to meet again in Hong
Kong on September 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
