<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schooling Restored in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Most universities, middle and
primary schools in Albania today formally restored schooling after
a two-month suspension caused by a sweeping unrest in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government has taken measures to protect the
universities and schools by sending armed personnel.
</P>
<P>
Myqerem Tafaji, Albanian minister of Higher Education and
Scientific Research, said today that unrest can't be allowed to
repeat and education should not discontinue.
</P>
<P>
All educational institutions were closed when President Sali
Berisha announced a state of emergency nationwide on March 2 after
chaos engulfed the Balkan nation due to the collapse of fraudulent
investment schemes, in which thousands of Albanian families lost
money.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people were killed and many schools and education
facilities were looted or smashed during the chaos.
</P>
<P>
Much of southern Albania is now still under the control of
armed protesters who insisted President Berisha resign over the
fraudulent investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
An Italian-led multinational force approved by the United
Nations is carrying out humanitarian relief operations in the
nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
