<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN FMs to Recommend New Membership Timing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 30 Xinhua) -- ASEAN foreign ministers will work
out a recommendation for their leaders on the timing of the
admission of Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar into the regional
grouping, according to Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn.
</P>
<P>
He said the heads of government of the seven ASEAN countries
would then have to make a final decision on the issue and make
either an official collective ASEAN announcement or individual
announcements of the entry date of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will make the political decision based on the
recommendation submitted by their foreign ministers, who will hold
an informal meeting on May 31, and the annual formal one in July,
both in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers will base their recommendation on the
ASEAN Secretariat's assessment report, which is being prepared, on
the situation and readiness of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN Foreign ministers will not make the decision, Prachuab
said in Phuket, where he is holding meetings with his Philippine
and Singaporean counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Late last year ASEAN leaders decided to grant full ASEAN
membership to the three countries simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Their entry has been hoped to take place this year as ASEAN
celebrates its 30th founding anniversary. The inclusion of all 10
countries in the region had been the goal of the ASEAN founders.
</P>
<P>
However, the three countries may not be considered ready for
their admission this year. Cambodia, for example, has not yet
passed legislation essential for its entry because of a row
between its co-prime ministers and domestic instability.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. government has exercised pressure on ASEAN
not to make Myanmar an ASEAN member because of what it calls
"woeful human rights performance."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN countries have announced that their decision on the three
countries' admission will not be influenced by the U.S. stance.
</P>
<P>
Among the three, Myanmar, as a member of the World Trade
Organization (WTO), is reported to be ready to integrate into the
ASEAN economic schemes -- ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA). Accession
to AFTA is the key criterion for ASEAN membership.
</P>
<P>
When asked of the possibility of the three candidates not
joining ASEAN this year, Saroj Chavanaviraj, Thai foreign ministry
permanent secretary, said, "Only if something very dramatic
happens."
</P>
<P>
He said ASEAN has its own way of deciding one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
One potential way could be "admission first, talks after"
(AFTA), some analysts say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Subjects for Technological Education in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will soon introduce new
subjects for technological education into the school curriculum to
keep abreast of international standards, Education Ministry
sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will hold In-service training sessions for
technical teachers on the new syllabus. A total of 225 teachers at
national level and 1,800 teachers at provincial level will be
trained for the task.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that some 725,000 US dollars for the purchase
of modern equipment needed for the project has been supplied by
the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The subjects that the students will be able to offer under the
new curriculum include agriculture, horticulture, animal
husbandry, food science and technology, inland aquatic
bio-research, construction technology, mechanics, electricity and
electronic technology, arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
The objective in introducing this program is to make students
aware of the importance of technological subjects and to pave the
way for the talented to enter the modern technology world, the
sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
