<HEADLINE> Mid-Term Election Likely in Nepal After Local Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's ruling partner and
biggest party in parliament may call a mid-term general election
if the local polls next month go in favor of the party, a top
party leader said.
</P>
<P>
President of the Communist party of Nepal (United Marxist
Leninist, CPN-UML) Man Mohan Adhikari Tuesday told reporters in a
district of southern Nepal, where he was on a campaign tour for
the forthcoming local elections, that his party might consider the
choice of mid-term polls if the local elections favor the party.
</P>
<P>
He also predicted an overwhelming victory for his CPN-UML party
in the local elections scheduled from May 17, according the local
press here today.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML hopes to win the control of over half of all the
4,000 local administration bodies at village, municipality and
district levels through next month's elections.
</P>
<P>
It currently holds less than one-third of all the local
authorities throughout the country while main opposition the
Nepali Congress (NC) party controls most of the rest.
</P>
<P>
The NC party, once the biggest and majority party in the
country, was overpowered in parliament by the CPN-UML through a
1994 mid-term election called by the then NC government.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML joined the present ruling coalition of Prime
Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand, a leader of the rather smaller
National Democratic Party (RPP), in early March when a NC-led
coalition government lost a confidence vote in the hung
parliament.
</P>
<P>
CPN-UML leaders believe that their party would become the
majority in parliament if a mid-term election be held.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
