<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Entry Not to Affect Hungary-Romania Ties: Roman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Relationship between Hungary and
Romania would not be affected if NATO decides to admit only one of
the two countries ahead of the other at its July summit, visiting
Chairman of Romanian Senate Petre Roman said today.
</P>
<P>
"It will not have a negative influence on bilateral ties if
NATO should accept only one of these two countries as a member at
its Madrid summit in July," Roman told reporters after a meeting
with his Hungarian counterpart, Gal Zoltan.
</P>
<P>
"But it would be unacceptable if it accepted none of these
two," Roman added. He arrived here Monday for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He said Hungary and Romania share common strategic aims and his
government would not change its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Gal agreed and said relationship between the two countries was
characterized by a breakthrough in establishing mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
Hungary would give its full support to Romania's admission to
NATO, Gal said.
</P>
<P>
In January 1994, NATO officially announced its expansion plan
to take in former Warsaw Pact member states from eastern and
central Europe. The Warsaw Pact was NATO's arch rival in the Cold
War era.
</P>
<P>
The plan has triggered strong opposition from Russia. However,
the 16-member alliance is expected to announce in July which
former Warsaw Pact member states are to be included in the first
wave of its enlargement, with Hungary, Poland and the Czech
Republic the front-runners.
</P>
<P>
Romania and Slovenia are considered as the next strongest
contenders.
</P>
<P>
Also today, when addressing Hungary's Elte University, Roman
reiterated that he believed his country would be one of the first
new NATO members.
</P>
<P>
NATO should avoid enlarging itself with discrimination, Roman
said. If excluding Romania, he said, the enlargement would only
result in a dismemberment in central Europe.
</P>
<P>
For central European countries, a NATO membership could help
lighten the burden caused by system transition and guarantee their
future development, Roman added.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Roman also said that without Russia, the
security of Europe was unimaginable, therefore, it was not allowed
to exclude Russia outside Europe. Apart from signing an agreement
with Russia, NATO should also attach importance to cooperation
with Ukraine, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
