<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> About 73 Million Children Work Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey made by the
International Labor Organization (ILO) estimates that 73 million
children under the age of 18 work throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
This figure does not include the number of girls who do
housework.
</P>
<P>
Although international organizations, such as ILO and the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), have made great efforts
for years to establish legal standards worldwide for minimum work
ages, the results have been modest.
</P>
<P>
In Venezuela alone, there are more than 350,000 children
between 10 and 17 who are working under poor conditions, said a
UNICEF report entitled "1997 World Situation of Children".
</P>
<P>
Another survey conducted by the National Institute of Minors
(INAM) on child labor reports that more than 72 percent of the
working children are not getting any legal protection because they
are normally working in the informal economic sector.
</P>
<P>
Most of them are exploited and exposed to dangerous situations
with work days that can be described as slavery, says the survey.
</P>
<P>
An average of 69.3 percent of them work double or triple shifts
and 61.5 percent work 6-7 days a week. On average, they work 5.4
days a week and 7.3 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 4.2 percent of the child laborers are involved in
activities that trespass the border between work and crime, like
prostitution.
</P>
<P>
Poverty, family breakdown, labor deregulation and the desire to
reduce costs to compete in a globalized world are reasons for
child labor.
</P>
<P>
In face of the serious situation, the Venezuelan government
prepared a plan of action in 1996 to protect children and improve
the working conditions of those who had to work to help support
their families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
