<HEADLINE> Venezuela's International Reserves Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's international
reserves fell to 15.583 billion U.S. dollars on April 21, a drop
of 303 million dollars from a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's international reserves were 15.461 billion dollars
in January, 15.807 billion dollars in February and 15.976 billion
dollars in March, according to Venezuela's Central Bank (BCV, its
acronym in Spanish).
</P>
<P>
However, the reserves have still risen 354 million dollars from
last year's close of 15.229 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the drop to the accelerated growth of
imports and the outlays for external commitments as well as
maturities of letters of credit and national debts.
</P>
<P>
Analysts also explained that the stability in the exchange rate
was one factor that encouraged purchases of foreign products.
</P>
