<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Ratifies Convention on Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Cuba ratified the United Nations'
Convention on Chemical Weapons Monday, a few hours before the
convention takes effect.
</P>
<P>
So far, Cuba is the 88th countries that ratified the treaty
which had been under negotiation for more than four years.
</P>
<P>
The instruments of ratification which became law on April
29 were deposited Monday night by Cuba's permanent mission to the
United Nations in the Treaty Section of the secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on the Prohibition of the Development,
Production, Storage and Use of Chemical Weapons and its
Destruction, the official name of the document, was open for
signing on January 13, 1993 in Paris by the then U.N.
Secretary-General Boutros Boutros Ghali.
</P>
<P>
It is the first disarmament agreement reached within a
multilateral framework that establishes the elimination of a
complete category of mass destruction weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
