<HEADLINE> NZ, Japanese Prime Ministers Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and New Zealand Prime Minister Jim
Bolger held what they both described as "frank and wide-ranging"
talks this morning.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after an hour-long
meeting, Bolger said NZ values its trade ties with Japan which is
NZ's second largest trading partner, but the two countries also
agree so much on many areas beyond trade.
</P>
<P>
Beside bilateral relations, he and Hashimoto also touched
matters including APEC, Japan's relations with the United States
and China.
</P>
<P>
Bolger said Japan supports the access to the Euro-Asian
dialogue by Australia and NZ, and NZ backs Japan's bid for
permanent membership in a reformed United Nation's Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
On the reforms NZ experienced a few years ago and now Japan has
expressed much interest, Bolger said he and Hashimoto agreed that
benefits will come at the end of reforms.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the conditions in NZ are different with those
in Japan, so the way of reforms in Japan should not be the same.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said the visit to NZ is "an element of the Asian-
Pacific diplomacy that I have vigorously promoted since taking
office."
</P>
<P>
He said he had a "frank exchange" of views with Bolger which
covered bilateral relations and regional matters.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the close relations between the two countries in
terms of economic and personnel exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Asked by a NZ journalist what assurance he has given to Bolger
about Japan's liberalization in agriculture to allow in more NZ
products, Hoshimoto's reply was not specific.
</P>
<P>
He said the most important issue is to implement step by step
the agreement of the Uruguay Round talks and Japan will not impose
restriction on any country.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon, Hashimoto, a keen mountaineer, will go for a
short walk in a forest park with Bolger near Wellington.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Prime Minister, who arrived here late last night,
will fly home tonight after attending a dinner at Bolger's house.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
