<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Build New Harbor in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka government has
decided to construct a new harbor in Colombo adjacent to the
present Colombo Port on an urgent basis to enable the country to
meet the challenges of the next century.
</P>
<P>
According to Shipping and Ports Ministry sources today, the
government has taken this decision in order to develop the Colombo
port technologically to meet the increasing market pressures.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that in line with demand studies, it is
estimated that the Colombo Port is required to increase capacity
by 4 million TEUs (containers) in the medium term and provide a
deeper basin capable of handling modern and larger ships.
</P>
<P>
It had also been decided to expand the present Queen Elizabeth
Quay of the Colombo Port to meet the short term capacity by 4
million TEUs in the medium term, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
The Master Plan for the brand new harbor in Colombo has been
approved by the government. It will be constructed on the southern
side of the existing Colombo Port.
</P>
<P>
The construction costs will be funded by traditional donor
countries and feasibility studies have already been prepared.
</P>
<P>
Volume handled in 1993 was 853,886 containers. It increased to
1,356,301 containers last year, according to the official
statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
