<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Malaysia Reach Accord on Islands Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Malaysia Tuesday
reached a special draft agreement on seeking a settlement of the
Sipadan and Ligitan islands dispute through the International
Court of Justice (ICJ), the official Antara news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the second senior officials
meeting between the two countries held in Bandung, West Java,
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian chief delegate Izhar Ibrahim and his Malaysian
counterpart Dato Andul Kadir Mohamad both said the Bandung meeting
has successfully and amicably drawn up a draft special agreement
which will be forwarded to the foreign affairs ministers of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Izhar Ibrahim said with the results that have been achieved,
the draft special agreement has been completed at senior officials
level.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, the document was not yet totally completed,
because amendments or changes were always possible after the draft
has been handed to the foreign ministers of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The first senior officials meeting (SOM) was held in Kuala
Lumpur in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
The SOM constituted a follow-up of an agreement between
Indonesian President Soeharto and Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Muhammad to settle the islands dispute before the ICJ in
the Hague.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders in their agreement reached in Kuala Lumpur in
October 1996 also stated that they would accept any judgment by
the ICJ.
</P>
<P>
The two tiny islands on the border between Serawak and
Kalimantan, have long been become a dispute between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The dispute is a 106-year-old legacy of the two countries'
former colonial rulers -- the Dutch in Indonesia and the British
in Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
