<HEADLINE> Jordan Named to Record Eighth All-Defensive First Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Chicago Bulls Michael Jordan
was selected to the NBA All-Defensive First Team for a
record-tying eighth time, the National Basketball Association
announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Only former Philadelphia and Denver star Bobby Jones was named
to as many NBA All-Defensive teams as Jordan, who was named on the
maximum 28 ballots in voting by the league's 29 head coaches.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was joinned on the 1996-97 NBA All-Defensive First Team
by Atlanta center Dikembe Mutombo, Seattle guard Gary Payton,
Chicago forward Scottie Pippen and Utah forward Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
The NBA All-Defensive Second Team consisted of Charlotte's
Anthony Mason and Miami's P.J. Brown at forward, Houston's Hakeem
Olajuwon at center and Atlanta's Mookie Blaylock and Utah's John
Stockton at guard.
</P>
<P>
Pippen led all players with 26 first-team votes and 53
points. Jordan, who was second with 23 first-team votes and 51
points, and Payton were the only players named on the maximum 28
ballots.
</P>
<P>
Two points were awarded for a first team vote and one for a
second team selection. Coaches were not permitted to vote for
players from their own team.
</P>
<P>
Pippen received the defensive accolade for the sixth time, and
Payton for the fourth, while Mutombo and Malone were newcomers to
the NBA All-Defensive First Team.  
</P>
</TEXT>
