<HEADLINE> Beijing To Attack Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's environmental
protection work this year will emphasize on air pollution
prevention and control, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing based newspaper quotes mayor Jia Qinglin as saying
that the municipality determines to abide by the State Council's
requirements on controlling the amount of pollutant discharge and
improving the urban environment by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Starting on June 1, petrol containing a large amount of lead
will be banned in eight urban districts of the capital. The use of
lead-free petrol is expected to reduce lead discharge into the air
by 46 tons this year. It will also enable the installation of
catalytic converters to remove pollutants from vehicle exhaust
gases.
</P>
<P>
The city's agencies in charge of public traffic and
environmental protection should also tighten inspections of auto
emissions. Other causes of air pollution also will be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 million cubic meters of natural gas will be piped into
the city from Shaanxi and Gansu provinces in 1998, which is
expected to eliminate 12,000 tons of sulphur dioxide and 36,000
tons of smog, improving the city's air quality, the paper
reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
