<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jakarta: U.S. Sanction on Myanmar to Be Ineffective </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has stated that the
U.S. sanction on Myanmar will be ineffective while ASEAN is still
considering Myanmar's bid to be admitted as a member without any
pressure from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Foreign Ministry spokesman Ghaffar Fadyl reiterated
here last night a statement made by Foreign Minister Ali Alatas in
Bangkok, Thailand, last week, that sanctions would not be relevant
or workable in the case of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN is a group of independent countries, so that other
countries can not put pressure on the group. Nobody knows better
than ASEAN itself what is good or bad for ASEAN," Fadyl noted.
</P>
<P>
Admitting Myanmar into ASEAN membership was a more effective
way to change the political and economic conditions in the country
than isolating Yangon from the international community, he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States stepped up its pressure on ASEAN (Association
of Southeast Asian Nations) last Friday by openly opposing
Myanmar's entry into ASEAN. Washington also announced economic
sanctions on Yangon as a condemnation of the military regime's
alleged human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, which groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, has declared that it
will admit Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos at the same time once they
meet the group's economic and other criteria.
</P>
<P>
The group, which is establishing a free-trade-area, has not set
a date, but analysts believe the three will be admitted this year
to mark ASEAN's 30th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Malaysia and Thailand had also brushed aside U.S.
economic sanctions on Myanmar and pledged to go ahead with ASEAN's
preparations to admit Yangon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (53-54) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (53-54) in
a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What governmental posts in the Hong Kong SAR must be
held by Chinese citizens?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Only Chinese citizens who are permanent residents of
the Hong Kong SAR with no right of abode in any foreign country and
have ordinarily resided in Hong Kong for a continuous period of
not less than 15 years may fill the following posts: Secretaries
and Deputy Secretaries of Departments, Directors of Buries,
Commissioner Against Corruption, Director of Audit, Commissioner
of Police, Director of Immigration and Commissioner of Customs and
Excise.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive of Hong Kong SAR must be a Chinese citizen
of not less than 40 years of age who is a permanent resident of
the region with no right of abode in any foreign country and has
ordinarily resided in Hong Kong for a continuous period of not
less than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Question: What posts are open for non-Chinese citizens among
permanent residents of the Hong Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Hong Kong is an international economic metropolis, and
many people not of Chinese nationality have held public service
posts. The future government of the Hong Kong SAR welcomes these
people to continue working in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, the government of the Hong Kong
SAR may employ foreign nationals serving previously as public
servants in Hong Kong or those holding permanent identity cards of
the SAR, to serve as public servants in government departments at
all levels, except for the following posts: Secretaries and Deputy
Secretaries of Departments, Directors of Buries, Commissioner
Against Corruption, Director of Audit, Commissioner of Police,
Director of Immigration and Commissioner of Customs and Excise.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government of the Hong Kong SAR may employ
foreign nationals as advisers to government departments and, when
required, may recruit qualified candidates from outside the SAR
to fill professional and technical posts in government departments.
</P>
<P>
The above provisions are reasonable. They not only embody
Chinese sovereignty over Hong Kong and the policy of "Hong Kong
people governing Hong Kong" but also dispel misgivings of
non-Chinese citizens among Hong Kong's public servants.
</P>
<P>
These provisions of the Basic Law will no double stabilize the
rank of public servants. But, more important, they aim to maintain
Hong Kong's prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
This policy is conducive to the economic development of Hong
Kong and to its developing trade and cultural exchanges with the
rest of the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
