<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Persian Ceramics Discovered in East China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Persian ceramics dating back to
the Tang Dynasty (618-907) have been found in some city ruins in
Ningbo city in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say that the city was one of four major
seaports in ancient China and that the find provides new evidence
of an ancient "ceramic road", similar to the "silk road", on the
sea.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that, from the 7th to the 18th century,
that a route ran from the Arab countries via the Persian Gulf, the
Indian Ocean, and Malaysia to Guangzhou (Canton) and from there to
Fuzhou in today's Fujian Province and Ningbo and Yangzhou in
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Persian ceramics have been found only in Fuzhou and
Yangzhou. The new finds, which date from the 8th or the 9th
century, are inferior in quality to Chinese porcelain made in the
Yueyao Kilns in Zhejiang, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
They assume, therefore, that the ceramics were not for trade
purposes but were articles brought to China by foreign business
people for their own use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
