<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Solicits Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 30 (Xinhua) -- This capital city of south
China's prosperous Guangdong Province yesterday announced 55
projects for overseas investment this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the projects, 31 are in the industrial sector, 10 in
infrastructure, seven in real estate and land development for
industrial purposes, three in agriculture and four in other
fields.
</P>
<P>
Companies from Singapore, Malaysia, Japan and Hong Kong today
signed six contracts and agreements with Guangzhou, which involved
a combined value of 143 billion US dollars, as well as one letter
of intent for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The projects announced cover the city's major industries in the
Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), according to Deputy Mayor
Chen Kaizhi.
</P>
<P>
Tan Kecheng, director of the Guangzhou City Commission of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said that, besides the
announced projects, overseas business people are also welcome to
invest in electronics, information, fine chemicals, biotechnology,
machinery, new materials and new energy sources.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou utilized 11.3 billion US dollars in overseas
investment and its registered number of overseas-funded projects
had reached 8,423 by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's use of foreign investment in the first quarter of
this year rose 7.1 percent on a yearly basis to 540 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The provincial capital has mapped out a plan to become an
international metropolis in the early years of the next century,
and one third of the funds needed will be raised overseas,
according to the officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
