<HEADLINE> FIFA Bans Chilavert and Asprilla </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Paraguayan goalkeeper Jose
Chilavert and Columbia striker Faustino Asprilla were banned from
competitions for their fighting during a World Cup match last
month, FIFA announced in Zurich Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chilavert received a four-match suspension and Asprilla was
banned for two after the pair came to blows during a qualification
match in Asuncion on April 2.
</P>
<P>
The incident triggered a melee involving players, both benches
and police that delayed the match for five minutes. Paraguay went
on to win 2-1, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Columbia's Victor Aristizabal was also suspended for three
matches and fined 5,000 Swiss Francs (3,390 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Argentine goalkeeper Ignacio Gonzalez and team mate Gustavo
Zapata were both suspended for three matches with compriot Nelson
Vivas for one for their part in a 10-minute scrap that erupted
during a 2-1 defeat by Bolivia in La Paz.
</P>
<P>
Jose Manuel Trujillo, the equipment manager for Bolivia has
been suspended permanently from all footballing activies and
Argentine coach Daniel Passarella was fined 10,000 Swiss francs.
</P>
<P>
The Bolivian Football Association was also fined 100,000 Swiss
Francs and Argentina 50,000, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
