<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fights Drug Addiction (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- A girl of only 20 years old,
Zhang has been addicted to drugs for three years. She sought help
in local hospitals or private clinics to quit drugs four
times, but never succeeded.
</P>
<P>
She is now in the Compulsory Rehabilitation Center under the
Beijing Municipal Public Security Bureau, where she was sent this
March after being caught by the local police while buying drugs.
</P>
<P>
"Now I hardly have the desire to take drugs, and have gained
eight kg here," said Zhang, who declined to give her full name.
</P>
<P>
Drug abuse is one of the social problems that have cropped up
in China since the 1980s. In 1995, China had some 520,000
registered drug addicts. The figure has been on the rise in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Baotong, deputy director of the Anti-Narcotics Office
under the Beijing municipal government, said that last year the
city found 904 local drug addict, up from 36 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government this month launched a nationwide
anti-drug campaign that is scheduled to last half a year. One
major goal of this campaign is to effectively reduce the current
number of drug addicts and control the emergence of new addicts.
</P>
<P>
Located in the suburban district if Fangshan some 60 km from
the downtown area, the Compulsory Rehabilitation Center under the
Beijing Municipal Public Security Bureau is the capital's only
medical institution that practices compulsory rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Four other hospitals in Beijing provide voluntary
rehabilitation for drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
Lu Qiulin, head of the center, said that her institution, which
was founded in early 1995, now houses a total of 132 drug addicts,
all directly sent from local public security departments.
</P>
<P>
"The compulsory rehabilitation usually takes three months, and
is divided into two phases -- physical rehabilitation and
psychological rehabilitation," said Lu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fights Drug Addiction (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The second phase, she said, mainly consists of health and legal
education, with the purpose of preventing cured addicts from
taking drugs again after their rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, we manage the patients in a semi-military manner,
which has reinforced the rehabilitation efforts," she added.
</P>
<P>
China's Minister of Public Security Tao Siju recently announced
that all drug addicts across the country are subject to compulsory
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
The country currently has 628 compulsory rehabilitation
centers, as well as 86 special reeducation-through-labor centers
that accommodate and provide rehabilitation for drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Zhao Baotong, the deputy director of the
center, it is more important for the anti-drug campaign to enable
the entire population to know about the danger of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that over 80 percent of the drug addicts in
China today are below the age of 35 years.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, the 20-year-old Beijing girl, recalled that she first
tried drugs because of curiosity and persuasion by her addicted
friends.
</P>
<P>
"I never imagined that a person could become addicted to drugs
so easily," she said regretfully. Having stayed at the center for
more than one month, she still looked ill and had a grey face.
</P>
<P>
Lu, the center manager, said that some 90 percent of her
patients became addicted because of ignorance about drugs and
curiosity.
</P>
<P>
Starting this year, especially since the beginning of April,
newspapers, magazines, and radio and television stations across
China have engaged in a major publicity drive against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Most frequently used in these reports is one short sentence --
"Cherish your life and keep away from drugs". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Ice" Seized for the First Time in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Customs has seized
for the first time 21.5 g of the narcotic "ice" from a package of
imported goods, a Customs source said.
</P>
<P>
Two anti-drug teams under the General Administration of Customs
found something unusual in a package when carrying out a routine
check on a batch of imported cargo April 16.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Customs put the item under close watch, but no
one claimed it until April 23, when an agent of the cargo's owner
came to take delivery of it. With the help of the departments
concerned, Customs officials had the package opened and found in
it a plastic bag hidden in packaging for metal parts for hydraulic
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The bag contained white crystals which turned out to be
deoxidized ephedrine, commonly known as "ice", which is a highly
addictive chemical compound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
