<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden and Finland Win at Ice Hockey Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Sweden maintained its winning
streak by beating Norway 4-1 on Tuesday at the ice hockey world
championship in group B played in Turku, Finland.
</P>
<P>
In Helsinki, Finland kept alive its hope of playing in the
final with an easy 6-0 win against Germany in Group A.
</P>
<P>
Sweden fell behind when Matts Trygg intercepted a long clearing
pass at the blue line and blasted a low slapshot past surprised
netminder Johan Hedberg.
</P>
<P>
But in the second period the Swedes moved ahead 2-1. Defenceman
Marcus Ragnarsson levelled the scores. Michael Nylander set up the
second for Per Eklund with a dazzling move.
</P>
<P>
Nylander sealed Norway's fate just 17 seconds into the final
period when he stole the puck from Jan-Roar Fagerli then broke in
alone on Schistad.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's victory left it at the top of the group with six
points. Norway have lost its opening three matches. Like Norway,
Germany have lost three opening games and both squads look certain
to travel to Tampere for the relegation play-offs next week after
the peliminary round-robin group games.
</P>
<P>
Finland leads group A with four points but still has to play
Russia and Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
Finland's game against a worn-out Germany resembled 60 minutes
of power-play. On Monday, Russia beat the Germans 5-1.
</P>
<P>
After Sunday's loss against titleholders the Czech Republic,
the win was important for Finland to enter the final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
