<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Geothermal Energy in Southwestern Part </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build a number of
medium-sized geothermal power stations in Tibet and the western
parts of Yunnan and Sichuan provinces by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to developing geothermal resources with
reservoir temperatures over 200 degrees centigrade in Yangbajing
of Tibet to increase the efficiency of power generation,
according to Zhang Qi, an energy expert at the Tianjin Geothermal
Research and Training Center.
</P>
<P>
The largest unit capacity in China is only three MWe now. In the
year 2000, the largest unit capacity in Yangbajing will reach
10MWe, he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country will build power stations with a
capacity of 3-5 MWe in Ruili in the western part of Yunnan
Province and explore the geothermal resources in Tengchong in
Yunnan and the western part of Sichuan Province by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
China has discovered 3,000 hot spring sites, about 2,200 of
which are higher than 25 degrees centigrade. High-temperature
resources, which formed two geothermal belts, are distributed
mainly in Tibet, Yunnan, and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The direct use of geothermal energy in China has a long
history. However, large scale exploration began only twenty years
ago. The total energy power utilization is about 2,410
MWt. Geothermal energy have been widely used in space heating,
industry, agriculture, and greenhouses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
