<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Day For China in Table Tennis Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China, which swept
all seven world titles in 1995, continued the dominance of table
tennis by taking the women's team event and booking a men's final
berth at the 44th World Championships on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese women trio led by world No. 1 Deng Yaping beat the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea to win the Corbillon Cup for
the 12th time, whearas their men players downed the South Koreans
in the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
China had an easy women's final since its top threats Japan and
South Korea had been knocked out in early rounds.
</P>
<P>
World No. 4 Yang Ying put China on the winning track as she
beat Wil Bok Sun in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Deng, who has bagged four Olympic gold medals,
had sent China 2-0 ahead with a convincing win over losing Olympic
semi-finalist Kim Hyon Hui before Li Ju won the third game against
Tu Jong Sil.
</P>
<P>
Chinese veteran Wang Tao, who delayed his retirement to check
South Koreans in the world championships, proved his value by
snatching two points from his longtime rivals at the men's
semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Wang, who has excellent record against South
Koreans, completed China's victory by nipping Kim Taek Soo in
three sets.
</P>
<P>
It was a sweet revenge for China, who has lost to South Korea
three times since the 1995 Worlds where it edged out South Korea
3-2 en route to winning the championship.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion Liu Guoliang put China one up as he
beat Kim in a clash of the world best penholders.
</P>
<P>
Wang had grabbed the second game from 72nd-ranked Ou Sang Eun
before Yoo Nam Kyu pulled back one point.
</P>
<P>
South Korean veteran Yoo Nam Kyu, ranked 19th in the world,
outplayed defending singles champion Kong Linghui 21-18, 10-21,
21-18.
</P>
<P>
Frenchmen reached their first-ever team final at the world
championships as Damien Eloi got the advantage of German Steffan
Fetzner in the deciding game.
</P>
<P>
Eloi, famed for his devastating forehand yet notorious for
inconsistency, displayed excellent poise and balance, employing
strong topspin strokes from both wings.
</P>
<P>
After taking the first set 21-15, the Frenchman widened the gap
to a usually unbeatable 17-8 and snatched the second set 21-11 to
seal France's victory.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Philippe Gatien, 1993 world champion now ranked 12th,
overcame midgame setbacks to beat Fetzner 26-24, 9-21, 21-17 at
the opening game.
</P>
<P>
Jorg Rosskopf, former European champion and Olympic bronze
medalist, evened the score with a 21-11, 21-18 triumph over Eloi.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Chila, rated 17th in the world, regained lead for
France as he downed Peter Franz 21-18, 21-13 in the third game.
</P>
<P>
Gatien failed to beat history as he lost the fourth game to
Rosskopf. The ninth-ranked German had beaten Gatien for eight
straight times before going into this match. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Makes Men's Team Final for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Damien Eloi nerved
himself in the deciding game against Germany, anchoring France
into its first-ever men's team final at the the World Table Tennis
Championships here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
World No. 29 Eloi beat more heralded Steffan Fetzner in
straight sets, putting France into the final clash with defending
champion China, which defeated South Korea 3-1 in the other
semi-final earlier.
</P>
<P>
Eloi, famed for his devastating forehand yet notorious for
inconsistency, displayed excellent poise and balance, employing
strong topspin strokes from both wings whereas 24th-ranked Fetzner
failed to reach his best form and looked nervous throughout the
game.
</P>
<P>
After taking the first set 21-15, the Frenchman widened the gap
to a nearly unbeatable 17-8 and snatched the second set 21-11 to
seal France's victory.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Philippe Gatien, 1993 world champion now ranked 12th,
overcame midgame setbacks to beat Fetzner 26-24, 9-21, 21-17 at
the opening game.
</P>
<P>
Jorg Rosskopf, former European champion and Olympic bronze
medalist, evened the score with a 21-11, 21-18 triumph over Eloi.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Chila, rated 17th in the world, regained lead for
France as he downed Peter Franz 21-18, 21-13 in the third game.
</P>
<P>
Gatien failed to beat history as he lost the fourth game to
Rosskopf. The ninth-ranked German had beaten Gatien for eight
straight times before going into this match.
</P>
<P>
Gatien got the first set 21-13 as the German was struggling to
find his form.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf, whose ferocious backhand is stronger than many of his
peer's forehands, came back strongly with lightning backhand flat
shots and split-second forehand attacks, winning the ensuing two
sets 21-16, 21-19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
