<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Calls on Voters to Vote for British Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major,
in his last-ditch effort to win Thursday's election, today called
on the voters to vote for the country's unity, sovereignty and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"This election is about the unity of the United Kingdom. It is,
literally, a battle for Britain.... If we lose, Britain will
change, yes -- change forever, change for the worse," Major told
the rally in east London, the last major campaign effort before
the election.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to fight right up to the last minute to keep our
economy booming, to stand firm in Europe and to keep our United
Kingdom one," added the prime minister, who is lagging far behind
the opposition Labor leader Tony Blair in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
Major said a Conservative victory would mean further steps
along the road to a prosperous Britain which his party had already
done much to build over the 18 years it has held power.
</P>
<P>
"The British people -- all the British people -- can go on to
reap the richest harvest we've ever known," he said.
</P>
<P>
The British economy has developed smoothly and healthily these
years with the unemployment rate down and inflation stable. But
the opinion polls show the voters are tired of the 18-year rule of
the Conservatives and want a change in the British politics.
</P>
<P>
Major stressed the importance of the voting which, he said,
would decide whether Britain's current economic success, based on
a low-tax, lightly regulated economy, would continue and whether
the country would escape the twin dangers of fragmentation into
its constituent nations and of the centralizing clutches of the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister earlier spent most of his last campaigning
day to attack the Labor party for their claims that another
Conservative government would scrap the state retirement pension
and put value added tax on food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
