<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Surges Back by 179 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
was flirting with its biggest-point gain ever today after a tame
reading on employment cost, a key force behind inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow soared by 179.01 to 6,962.03. It was the third Tuesday
in a row that the Dow broke the record for its second-biggest
point gain after a 186.84-point gain that came two days after the
Black Monday crash of 1987.
</P>
<P>
Today, the Dow once made a nearly 188-point gain that would
have been the biggest ever for the blue-chip barometer.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 4-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where NYSE volume totaled
547.67 million shares, much more than 402.42 million in the
previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list jumped 21.09 points to
794.05, and the NYSE's composite index rose 9.94 to 413.63.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 25.61 to 1,242.64, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 6.83 to 548.03.
</P>
<P>
The rally put the Dow within striking distance of 7,000 for the
first time since the start of a nearly 700-point retreat from its
March 11 high of 7,085.16. The Dow has now recovered more than 500
points of that one-month slide.
</P>
<P>
Stocks also gained strength from the bond market, where
interest rates plunged below 7 percent, a psychologically
important barrier after the Labor Department reported that
Americans' wages and benefits rose a modest 0.6 percent in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The enthusiasm over today's employment cost data was bolstered
by two separate reports suggesting that other inflationary
pressures may be easing.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department reported that factory orders for
big-ticket durable goods unexpectedly plunged 3 percent in March,
the biggest decline in seven months. The Conference Board research
group, meanwhile, reported that consumer confidence dropped for
the second straight month in April.
</P>
<P>
Investors have been worried that without signs of economic
moderation, the Fed will raise rates again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
