<HEADLINE> US Dollar Retreats on Weaker Economic Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell today for
the first time in nearly a week after new data suggested an
unexpected slowdown in economy, reducing possibility the Federal
Reserve will raise interest rates at its May meeting.
</P>
<P>
The surprisingly tame economic reports led to strong rallies in
the stock and bond markets and sent the Dow Jones industrial
average up 179.01 points, its second biggest point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
But the data sent the dollar down at the foreign exchange
market where investors locked in profits on the currency's recent
gains.
</P>
<P>
The dollar settled at 1.7243 marks, down from 1.7330 Monday.
The dollar cost 126.87 yen, down from 126.98. The pound cost
1.6316 U.S. dollars, up from 1.6247 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday:
5.8120 French francs, down from 5.8385; 1.4675 Swiss francs, down
from 1.4740; 1,707.00 Italian lire, down from 1,718.00; 1.3977
Canadian dollars, down from 1.3998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
