<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Admits Turkey's Eligibility for EU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) today
said that it recognized the eligibility of Turkey for EU full
membership after intensive talks with Turkish Prime Minister Tansu
Ciller in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek, EU commissioner for relations with central and
eastern Europe, told a press conference today that the meeting
with Turkey had shown the importance the EU attached to EU-Turkish
relations.
</P>
<P>
Both sides emphasized their concern over the Customs Union
between Turkey and the EU, which entered into force on December
31, 1995, saying that it had to be further developed.
</P>
<P>
Ciller today expressed her disappointment over "a lack of
cooperation" from Greece, which maintained its veto on the EU's
financial aid of 375 million ECUs (some 450 million U.S. dollars)
to Ankara.
</P>
<P>
However, Greece and Turkey have agreed to appoint about two
personalities each, non-governmental and not necessarily nationals
of the two countries, to consider the position and submissions of
both governments on issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Ciller said that this was "a step forward in the right
direction," which could help study ways of solving issues
presented by both countries.
</P>
<P>
The Association Council, which Turkey and the EU called their
meeting today, had been boycotted by Greece for 18 months before
it took place in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the EU also raised issues which it said Turkey
should take into consideration if it wanted to further strengthen
its relationship with the EU. The issues included human rights,
rule of law and fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Saying they had conducted "very good" talks, both sides of the
meeting indicated that Turkey's accession to the EU should be
achieved on a step-by-step basis.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government, which has been working hard to pursue
the EU membership, said that Turkey should be judged by the same
criteria in which the EU member states were being judged. It asked
for an "equal and fair" judgement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
