<DOCNO> XIE19970430.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Not to Be Sidelined by EMU, Says Major </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
said today his country would not be sidelined at international
economic summits if it did not join the European Economic and
Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Conservatives' last election rally before the
May 1 election, Major said London was one of the major financial
centers in the world and Britain would maintain its important role
in world economic policy.
</P>
<P>
"London is one of the financial centers of the world, and will
stay that way. The suggestion that the European Union would take
over all representation on economic policy for members of the
single currency is just the kind of danger I have been warning
about," Major said, adding he "would never accept that."
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in response to suggestions by European
commissioner for monetary union Yves Thibault de Silguy that a G3
summit consisting of America, Japan and the European Union would
replace the G7 summits of the world's major economic nations,
describing it as "absurd and arrogant."
</P>
<P>
The EMU will be launched on January 1, 1999 and those EU
countries which fail to reach the criteria of keeping their budget
deficits below 3 percent of the gross domestic product are allowed
to join the single currency later.
</P>
<P>
Major has adopted a policy of "wait and see" about joining a
single European currency. The opposition Labor party, which is set
to replace the Conservatives in Thursday's election, also promises
a referendum on whether to join the EMU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
